<HEAD>Erin's Winds Easingd, Storm's Weakening Forecast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with 10:30 p.m. EDT position; picks
up 4th graf pvs: `The storm ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hurricane Erin continued its northward trek into cooler mid-Atlantic waters Friday with winds falling to 85 mph and forecasters predicting a gradual weakening over the weekend. `` It's only a threat to marine interests,'' said National Hurricane Center forecaster <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> Kimberlain </PERSON>. `` Our forecast track is between <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>.'' At 10:30 p.m. EDT, <PERSON> Erin </PERSON>'s center was near 43.0 north latitude and 35.4 west longitude, or about 310 miles west-northwest of the westernmost <LOCATION> Azores </LOCATION>. The system was moving northeast at about 25 mph and was expected to weaken gradually over the next 24 hours. The storm will probably lose its tropical characteristics over the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>, but that does n't mean it will be harmless, <PERSON> Kimberlain </PERSON> said. The storm will probably lose what forecasters call its tropical characteristics over the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>, but that does n't mean it will be harmless, <PERSON> Kimberlain </PERSON> said. A similar storm lashed <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> two years ago, causing substantial damage. <PERSON> Erin </PERSON> became a named storm Sunday night when sustained winds reached 39 mph. It reached the 74 mph threshold for a hurricane Tuesday. There have been seven tropical depressions in the 1989 <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> hurricane season, which runs from June 1 to Nov. 30. <PERSON> Erin </PERSON> is the fifth named storm and the third hurricane of the year.
