<HEAD>Abbreviated Test Flight Blamed On Defective Part</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The second test flight of the B-2 stealth bomber was scrubbed in midflight because of a crack in a part provided by a defense contractor once fined for billing fraud, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> officials said. A hairline crack in a casing of an accessory drive, which powers the $ 530 million high-tech jet's generators and controls, caused oil pressure to drop during the Aug. 16 test flight, Air Force Capt. <PERSON> Tess </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> said Thursday. `` It was n't anything critical that would have caused the plane to crash,'' she said. `` It was a minor problem.'' The flight of the bat-wing bomber designed to pass through enemy radar undetected was scheduled to last up to four hours, but was halted after about one hour. The casing for the aircraft's No. 1 accessory drive was made by <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Rockford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, which <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials indefinitely suspended last year from doing business with the government. <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> was fined $ 115 million in October for overcharging the government for parts, billing the Pentagon for baby-sitting costs, country club dues and executive servants. The suspension did not affect contracts the company already had, including the one for the B-2 casings. <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> said he would not comment on the flaw. The part was redesigned to make it thicker after laboratory tests indicated the casing would work better if strengthened, Ms. <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> said. `` There's absolutely nothing wrong with the part as originally designed,'' she said. `` Things break, OK?'' Officials for <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which builds the B-2, said the thinner casings, measuring four feet long, one foot wide and five inches thick, were examined and cleared as airworthy. `` We would n't put anything in there that we thought was potentially defective,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>'s B-2 spokesman <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Cantafio </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> engineers continue to work with designers from <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> and other subcontractors throughout the B-2 construction process and were fully aware of the modifications made to thicken the casing, Ms. <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Cantafio </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> both said they were unaware of any plan to replace the thinner parts before the B-2's next test flight. The government has spent about $ 22.4 billion in the B-2 program, which is 18 months behind schedule, and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has balked at the thought of paying more than $ 500 million apiece for 132 bombers. Shrouded in secrecy for 10 years, <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> last month began an intensive campaign to surmount stealth foes. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> wants $ 4.7 billion for the bomber in the coming fiscal year, and it may need $ 8 billion in each of the three years of peak production, 1992 to 1994.
</TEXT>
