<HEAD>Court Rules Boston Can Close Five Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A state appeals court ruled Friday that five <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> public schools at the heart of a fierce dispute over budget-cutting can be closed. Schools Superintendent <PERSON> Laval </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said the five schools will be closed as planned and affected parents will receive new school assignments for their children. On July 25, the city's school committee voted to close the schools to meet Mayor <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>'s $ 362 million target budget and to ease a projected $ 2.6 million deficit going into the school year. The three-judge <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> panel ruled that the school committee's vote was valid, even though it erred when a required public hearing was delayed until Aug. 7. Parents who had fought the closings said they did not expect to appeal Friday's decision, which overturned a <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> Superior Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roseman </PERSON>'s decision Tuesday to block the closing plan. <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Cappucci </PERSON> said he preferred saving money by closing the schools rather than putting special programs like athletics `` on the chopping block.'' `` I would rather close buildings than programs,'' said <PERSON> Cappucci </PERSON>. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said the committee has made $ 3 million in administrative staff cuts.
