<SECOND>AM-Florida-Crackdown, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0715,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Arrested In Second Statewide Anti-Crack Push</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with arrest, seizure totals; picks
up 5th graf: `The 48-hour ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s second sweep of drug users and dealers netted more than 1,400 arrests by Friday evening as authorities combined reverse sting and `` Trojan Horse'' operations with search warrants and highway surveillance. `` I think the idea is to just get as much crack off the street as we can, and to once again send a message to people that are buying and selling crack that it's not going to be tolerated,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Liljedal </PERSON>, spokesman for the <LOCATION> Broward </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff's office. By 11:00 p.m. Friday, the roundup produced 6,683 crack cocaine rocks, 2.6 pounds of cocaine powder, 10.44 pounds of marijuana, 52 firearms, 209 vehicles and $ 54,667 in cash. A total of 1,465 arrests had been made by Friday evening in the operation, staffed by an estimated 1,200 officers in all of the state's 67 counties. The 48-hour crackdown, dubbed Operation Rock Pile II, was launched at 12:01 a.m. Thursday and was coordinated by the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriffs </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. A total of 2,076 arrests were made in the first Operation Rock Pile, begun June 31. It also netted 3,510 crack cocaine rocks, 10 pounds of cocaine powder, 3 pounds of marijuana, 327 vehicles, 50 firearms and $ 55,107 cash. Crack, a derivative of cocaine, is sold in small chunks called rocks. `` The only thing that surprised us intially was what seemed to be an unsually high amount of marijuana,'' <PERSON> Liljedal </PERSON> said at the operation's command post in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>. In reverse stings, officers pose as drug sellers and bust customers. In Trojan Horse operations, several deputies ride hidden in the back of a truck and jump out to make arrests when the driver is offered crack for sale by street corner dealers. `` Nothing seems to deter these people when they're looking for crack or looking to sell it,'' said <PERSON> Liljedal </PERSON>.
