<SECOND>AM-Snowmobile Shooting,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cameron Kocher, 10, Arraigned On Homicide Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STROUDSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 10-year-old boy pleaded innocent Friday to adult charges of criminal homicide in the March shooting of a 7-year-old girl who was riding a snowmobile in a lot adjacent to his home. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> <PERSON> Kocher </PERSON> was 9 years old when, police said, he loaded his father's .35 - caliber rifle, pointed it out his parent's bedroom window and shot <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> of <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> in the He has been free on $ 50,000 bail. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> stood silently next to his attorney as Monroe County Judge <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vican </PERSON>, addressing the boy as `` Mr. <PERSON> Kocher </PERSON>,'' explained the charges of criminal homicide, aggravated assault and recklessly endangerment. Defense attorney <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansford </PERSON> signed documents indicating <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON>'s plea while the boy looked on, and told the judge he had instructed the boy to stay quiet. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> stood before the judge with his arms folded, occasionally looking at the ceiling and let out a heavy sigh as he turned to his parents after the proceedings ended. <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> was riding on the back of a snowmobile March 6 in <LOCATION> Kresgeville </LOCATION> with her friend and <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON>'s next-door neighbor, <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratti </PERSON>, 13, when she was shot. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> was arrested two days later after police found the rifle with a telescopic sight, a cut on the boy's forehead and blood splattered in the room. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> said the rifle cut him when its recoil jammed the scope's eyepiece into his face. In June, <PERSON> Vican </PERSON> refused to transfer <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON>'s case to juvenile court, saying the shooting was deliberate. <PERSON> Vican </PERSON>'s decision followed four days of testimony from psychologists hired by the Kochers and the state. <PERSON> Vican </PERSON> wrote in June that all four psychotherapists who examined <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> agreed he did not have any mental or emotional problems at the time of the shooting. The psychologists disagreed, however, on whether <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> could understand the proceedings and participate in his defense. The also disagreed on whether he could form the intent to kill. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> faced a pre-arraignment shortly after his arrest in March, when bail was set at $ 50,000. He has been free on bond since then. Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Pazuhanich </PERSON> said in an interview he has ruled out seeking the death penalty. He said if the boy is convicted, punishment could range from probation in conjunction with psychiatric treatment, to life imprisonment. The defense has 30 days to file pre-trial motions.
