<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia-DrugLords     08-26 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Drug Lords,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Medieval-Style Castle Shows Drug Lords' Fast-Lane Philosophy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHIA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Why waltz when you can rock' n' roll?'' wrote a visitor in the guest book at the medieval-style castle of reputed cocaine trafficker <PERSON> Camilo </PERSON> <PERSON> Zapata </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasquez </PERSON>. The question reflects the fast-lane philosophy obviously embraced by <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s wealthy drug lords, and was revealed in the public confiscation of hundreds of their properties nationwide in an anti-narcotics crackdown. The sandstone castle, ringed by formal gardens, dominates a 200-acre compound of 10 buildings, a dozen thoroughbred horses as well as goats, ducks, dogs and even a couple of flamingos. Visible from a nearby highway, it has long been a landmark in <LOCATION> Chia </LOCATION>, a suburb 13 miles north of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. It was seized by the army this week, and shown off to reporters on Friday. European and Oriential antiques filled the castle's richly appointed rooms, lined with paintings, statues and ceramic figurines. Beds were framed with crystal and bronze, or four towering posters with marble bedside tables filled with electronics to open and shut doors and control video equipment. A guest book provided a peek at the peculiar variety of people who visited the estate. It is just one of many believed to have been owned by <PERSON> Zapata </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasquez </PERSON>, even though he is considered a kind of second-string smuggler, lacking the household-name stature of reputed cartel bosses such as <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Escobar </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Ochoa </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gonzalo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Gacha </PERSON>. The visitor who endorsed rock' n' roll signed his message, apparently in jest, `` M-19 power.'' M-19 is the name accorded to a leftist guerrilla group operating in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, although the traffickers are much more closely associated with right-wing death squads. Another visitor, calling himself <PERSON> Mad </PERSON> <PERSON> Max </PERSON>, wrote: `` Living by chance, loving by choice and killing by profession.'' An Oct. 10, 1988, visitor named <PERSON> Tuti </PERSON> wrote in a feminine hand: `` Happy birthday. Tomorrow they'll kill me and it'll be your fault.'' Many women left their phone numbers after their signatures. <PERSON> Margarita </PERSON> <PERSON> Zapata </PERSON>, identified by army officials on the estate as <PERSON> Zapata </PERSON>'s sister, was much more solemn: `` May God and the Virgin bless all of this and those who inhabit it.'' The book also was signed by two men who identified themselves as local police station commanders, two army lieutenants and an army captain. Two local mayors also signed, one of them declaring, `` Few people can truly appreciate the history of this property.'' A group of women from several embassies, including <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> signed the book, as did a tour from a religious society. Next door to the estate is a religious boarding school run by nuns. In a garage and sprawling servants' quarters attached to the castle were two new Mercedes automobiles, also confiscated. There were also stables, where an office wall was lined with ribbons and trophies; an indoor swimming pool and gym, tennis courts, horse exercise trails and a modern thatch-roofed cottage of many rooms. There was a chapel as well, dedicated to <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Assisi </LOCATION>, with stained glass windows, antique religious statues and pews for about 30 people. Studiously ignoring the dozens of soldiers who guarded the place were 10 groundskeepers who watered the well-kept lawns and acres of gardens, trimmed the hundreds of yards of hedges and tended to the animals. They gave contradicting statements about <PERSON> Zapata </PERSON> <PERSON> Vasquez </PERSON>: he never came to stay, he came regularly, he just left a couple of weeks ago. They all agreed on one thing: they were underpaid, receiving the minimum legal wage _ about $ 80 a month.
