<FIRST>u i PM-Austria-Refugees Bjt   08-26 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Austria-Refugees, Bjt,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Europeans Get Help, but Pose Problems for Austria</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOERBISCH, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The hospitality extended for 40 years by this haven for Soviet bloc refugees is being strained as more East Europeans take advantage of reforms and emigrate to the West. While East Germans flooding across the Austro-Hungarian border this summer have enjoyed heartfelt welcomes, other East European refugees find state support withering away. Women in the border town of <LOCATION> Moerbisch </LOCATION> have spent days sorting old clothes, cooking and giving hugs to exhausted East Germans who stumble in after a grueling journey to freedom through the borderland brush. `` You just have to help. Anyone with a sense of humanity has to,'' said one woman, her eyes filling with tears as she surveyed the large hall where tables were piled high with clothes and dazed East Germans sat over sausages and bread. `` I remember in 1956, my husband drove down to the border day and night with his truck to pick up the refugees,'' she said on condition of anonymity, recalling the mass exodus of Hungarians after Soviet tanks crushed <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s anti-Stalinist uprising. In 1968, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> sheltered streams of Czechoslovaks after other <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact countries crushed the `` Prague Spring'' reforms. And when martial law was declared in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in 1981, at least 35,000 Poles sought asylum here. <PERSON> Ilse </PERSON> <PERSON> Tremmel </PERSON>, chief organizer of <PERSON> Moerbisch </PERSON>'s relief program, is full of energy, seeing that volunteers get rest and giving a mother's firm hug to a 17-year-old boy who left his childhood and his parents on the other side of the East-West divide. `` The help has come from everywhere,'' she says. `` Private individuals, companies, stores. Everyone is helping.'' The East Germans spend only days in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> before going to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. But thousands of Poles and Hungarians want to remain, and because of that they feel less welcome. Their asylum applications now are rejected on grounds they are not politically persecuted but seek only to improve their economic situation. Refugee <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mojzer </PERSON> does n't see the distinction. `` You ca n't separate the two,'' he says `` If the -LRB- communist -RRB- party regulates everything, then you ca n't live or work freely.'' Many Austrians believe the Hungarians and Poles sponge off the state, receiving free room and board plus meager monthly allowances while they wait years for applications to be processed. But in July and August, 3,800 Hungarians and Poles stopped receiving the allowances and were turned out of government-rented hotels and boarding houses. They came to <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> before May 1988, when the Austrian government began rejecting most asylum applications. Interior Minister <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Loeschnak </PERSON>, under fire from left-wingers who argue this violates <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s policy of sheltering all refugees, insisted the Poles and Hungarians were informed months in advance. But many said they were given only days' notice. About 800 jobs and language training for some Poles and Hungarians was arranged to end the furor. But <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, and the West in general, still faces the dilemma of absorbing tens of thousands of East Europeans expected to cross increasingly open borders. <PERSON> Pius </PERSON> <PERSON> Strobl </PERSON>, a leader of the small opposition Green-Alternative party, noted that 10 percent of <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s population of 7.4 million are former refugees. <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s declining population should encourage authorities to integrate new arrivals who are anxious to work, he said. Two million refugees have come here since World War II ended and 613,000 remain, officials say. Last year, 16,000 applications for asylum were submitted, double the number for 1986. Hungarians who refuse to return home and depend on charitable organizations complain they are trapped in a Catch-22 situation _ needing a work permit to secure a residence permit, and a permanent place of residence to acquire a work permit. `` Who can guarantee that the reforms in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> will continue,'' asked <PERSON> Ferenc </PERSON> <PERSON> Briski </PERSON>, who came to <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> in 1987. <PERSON> Briski </PERSON>'s family is among several that found lodging in eastern <LOCATION> Burgenland </LOCATION> province with help from the Greens and charity groups. Some live without electricity or heating. Hungarian-born <PERSON> Wilma </PERSON> <PERSON> Csoknyai </PERSON> recalls when she came to <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> after World War II and how impressed she was with the hospitality. `` After the war, when nobody had anything, it was apparently easier to be a refugee,'' she said. `` Now people ca n't imagine how it is to have nothing.''
