<HEAD>Library of Congress to Combat Damage in Leningrad's Great Collection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> said today it has received $ 135,000 to help restore fire - and water-damaged books in a <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> institution where one of the worst library disasters in history occurred The gift from Reader's Digest will help experts counter the damage at the <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION>, whose collection of 20 million books, manuscripts and periodicals was begun in 1714 by <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> the Great. Four million books were damaged or destroyed in a 19-hour fire in February 1988. The Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is a leader in developing techniques to rescue books threatened by decay or disaster. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Billington </PERSON>, librarian of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and a <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> expert, went to <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> after the fire to assess the damage and arranged for a protocol, signed by the two institutions, agreeing to preserve damaged materials and replace destroyed books. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Waters </PERSON>, a Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> expert on the conservation of damaged book collections, went to <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> within six weeks of the fire. <PERSON> Billington </PERSON> welcomed the gift, saying in a statement that it underscored the principle that library collections `` are truly international resources for humanity which all of us must support whenever one of them is threatened by destruction.'' The library said the Reader's Digest grant will finance equipment, supplies and technical consultation to return to use many of the 200,000 rare volumes that were frozen in an effort to arrest deterioration after the fire. The <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> institution is one of the world's largest research libraries, although not nearly as large as the <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, which holds 86 million items. The Academy Library is a major exchange partner for most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> research libraries that collect Russian and Soviet materials. Every year, several hundred <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> specialists in <LOCATION> Russians </LOCATION> affairs visit there to do research. A few months after the fire, Soviet historian and cultural activist <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> Likhachev </PERSON> said the disaster could have been prevented if officials had heeded warnings about the dilapidated condition of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s most prestigious book collections. He said it pained him to see how rare books and art treasures that were spirited away by residents of <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> to protect them from Nazis who occupied the city in World War II had been destroyed through negligence.
