onth requiring traders to reduce their holdings in soybean futures contracts. That decision touched off wild swings in soybean prices and sparked sharp criticism by farm groups, and traders saw the value of their futures holdings drop. Those who had sold borrowed soybean futures on speculation the price would fall, in what's known as a short position, stood to gain from the emergency order because it resulted in a steep drop in soybean prices. The Board of Trade has said it took the action after consulting with the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>, because a subsidiary of Italian grain merchant <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finanziaria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.P.A. </ORGANIZATION>, failed to voluntarily reduce its large holdings in the July soybean market. <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION> officials have said the exchange was worried that soybean supplies were insufficient for meeting large holdings of contracts for July delivery of soybeans in the final days of trading in that contract. The July 11 order requiring traders to reduce their positions in the July soybean market to 1 million bushels was widely perceived as a move to prevent <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> from cornering the soybean market, which <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> has denied. <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> also has bitterly criticized the CBOT action. `` We continue to believe that is was totally unnecessary for the board to take its emergency action,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON>, an executive with <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> subsidiary. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> supports Sen. <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>'s call for further investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> into the matter,'' said <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON>, also chief executive officer of <ORGA