<HEAD>Ex-Harvard Student Sentenced for Armed Robberies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LYNN ELBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A young man from a poor, Hispanic neighborhood who went on to attend <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> was sentenced to 10 years in prison for six armed robberies committed during school breaks. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Razo </PERSON>, 22, was convicted in June of six robberies and attempting to escape police after his 1987 arrest in <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. He was found innocent of four other robberies. `` He's earned his way to <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, but he also earned his way to prison,'' Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> Ravi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mehta </PERSON> told the court before sentencing. `` Mr. <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> needs to pay his dues to society now. Mr. <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> needs to be punished for what he's done.'' <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> also faces trial in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, where he is charged with three counts of robbery and six of assault with a deadly weapon. `` I have not disregarded the good things I have learned about you, Mr. <PERSON> Razo </PERSON>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Rheinheimer </PERSON> said before she sentenced <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> on Friday. `` This is not a happy sentencing for this court.'' Rheinheimer, who could have given him a maximum 15-year term, was asked by the defense to consider <PERSON> Razo </PERSON>'s achievements as a star athlete and scholar who gave time to charity. `` I do n't know how it is that a boy such as <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> stands before this court facing 15 years in state prison,'' said attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON>. `` Perhaps the gap between the barrio of <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Habra </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> was just too wide for him to pass.'' But <PERSON> Rheinheimer </PERSON> said she could not ignore the fact the crimes were premeditated and occurred over a two-year period, showing what she called a `` pattern of conduct dangerous to society.'' Each of the 10 store robberies, committed between December 1985 and June 1987, occurred during school breaks while he attended <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> for two years. <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> sat expressionless Friday as the sentence was read. His tearful parents refused to comment. `` What can we say?'' <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON> said he planned an appeal. He called the sentence too severe, but added, `` The judge gave her honest opinion of what the crimes were worth and what the defendant was worth.'' With credit for time served and for good behavior, <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> could be eligible for release in about three years, <PERSON> Mehta </PERSON> said outside court. <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> will then face three years on parole. A $ 500 fine also was imposed. <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> was a former high school football star, <ORGANIZATION> Boys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> `` Boy of the Year'' and outstanding student at <ORGANIZATION> Servite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Anaheim </LOCATION>. The prosecution's case relied heavily on a videotaped confession in which <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> recounted with vivid detail the crimes, each committed by a gunman wearing a ski mask. The holdups at fast-food restaurants, grocery and drug stores, netted the gunman $ 27,000. <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> later retracted the confession, saying he was in a drug-induced stupor. He claimed he was describing crimes actually committed by a friend.
