<HEAD>Schroeder Says Philippines Shouldn't Expect Large Sums of U.S. Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> Democrat who heads the panel that funds <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases, says the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> will have `` a long wait coming'' if they expect large sums of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid. Her comments came as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> prepare to start negotiations on renewing six military base leases that expire in 1991. Many Filipino lawmakers are demanding far higher <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid in return, or a phased withdrawal of American forces. <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON>, just back from a 16-day trip to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, said the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> wants $ 2 billion each year. `` I told them that if they are waiting for foreign aid to more than double, they have a long wait coming,'' she said in a statement Friday. Her sentiments have been echoed in recent weeks by other lawmakers visiting the region over the summer recess. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> agreed to pay the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> some $ 960 million until 1991, but <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> said she would introduce a bill to sever the link between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign aid for the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> base rights there. `` Either a base is necessary for mutual defense or it is not,'' she said. <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> also issued a report she commissioned from the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the watchdog agency of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, which said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> could save the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> $ 600 million annually by assuming payments in Japanese yen for such things as utility bills and salaries of Japanese workers on the bases. The report also disputed <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s claim that it can not increase support for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces without renegotiating the 1960 agreement for the stationing of American troops there. `` The Japanese are hiding behind this document, and our government lets them get away with it,'' <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> said. The study praised <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for increasing its share of funding for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces from 24 percent in 1981 to 31 percent or $ 1.7 billion in 1987. But it said much of the gain resulted from the fact that the stronger yen now buys more dollars. `` Although the increase in Japanese support from 1981 to 1987 is impressive when measured in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars, much of it can be attributed to the decline of the dollar's value against the yen,'' the report said. When measured in dollars, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s cash contributions rose 137 percent, but because of the strengthening of the yen, the actual increase was 44 percent, the study found.
