<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This year's filbert harvest in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is estimated at 13,500 tons, down 18 percent from 1988 and the smallest output since 1984, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says. The Oregon crop of filberts, or hazelnuts, was forecast at 13,300 tons, compared with 16,300 tons in 1988. The <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> harvest was indicated at 200 tons, the same as last year. Officials said filbert trees, particularly of the <ORGANIZATION> Barcelona </ORGANIZATION> variety, were hurt by severe cold in early February during their crucial pollination stage. `` As a result, nut set is lighter than in 1988,'' said Friday's report `` Also, growers report a larger-than-normal number of blanks. Nut size, however, is up significantly from last year.''
