<SECOND>PM-Pipeline Safety,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inspectors to Probe Train Derailment-Explosion Disasters in Hearings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Maybe it's just her imagination, but <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> swears the train rumbling by her home has been louder since those hellish days in May when a train derailment was followed by a fiery pipeline explosion. `` It's like you stop every time the train passes to make sure nothing's happening. During the night it's just twice as loud,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, one of dozens of residents still looking for explanations and blame for the twin disasters. Beginning Monday, some of their questions may be answered when the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> begins five days of hearings into the May 12 derailment of a <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> freight train and the May 25 explosion of a <ORGANIZATION> Calnev </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> gasoline line near the tracks. The two disasters killed six people and destroyed 15 homes, focusing new attention on pipeline safety. The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> hearing is intended to gather information to help the board determine a cause of the disasters and to make recommendations to prevent further accidents, said board spokesman <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON>. The board will pursue how workers calculated the load weight on the train, the quality of locomotive brakes, the cleanup of train wreckage near the Calnev pipeline and the effectiveness of check valves in the line. A final report, with the probable cause, is expected in at least six months. In the meantime, ` We're just kind of in limbo,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, whose house escaped serious damage but who continues to see a psychologist to help her deal with the emotional trauma caused by the disasters. The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> hearing marks the latest in a series of public hearings probing the disasters. In earlier sessions, government officials called the nation's pipeline safety programs inadequate, while industry officials responded by pointing to the industry's relatively good safety record Some of the sharpest criticism of the government's role in pipeline safety has come from <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> lawmakers who say regulators are burdened by staff shortages, out-of-date equipment and a tangle of weak and confusing laws. The state's Pipeline Safety Division, which acts as the federal government's surrogate in pipeline regulation, employs 12 people to oversee thousands of miles of lines. Officials acknowledged that for several hours after the derailment they did n't even know of the existence of the Duffy Street pipeline, which supplies 90 percent of <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>' gas and nearly all the jet fuel to <PERSON> George </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> air force bases. The federal Office of Pipeline Safety said the <LOCATION> Calnev </LOCATION> line may not have exploded after the train derailment had authorities been given the power to order a pressure test on the line to search out leaks and weak spots. <PERSON> Calnev </PERSON> did not perform the test, saying it did not appear necessary at the time. Three check valves in the pipeline uphill from the rupture failed to close after the blast and gasoline flowed back into the flames, <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> inspectors found. Investigators discovered that the valves had not been inspected or maintained since they were installed along with the pipeline in 1970. Calnev has since inspected its valves and taken other steps in the wake of disasters, said spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kline </PERSON>. <PERSON> Calnev </PERSON>, like other pipeline companies, vigorously defends its practices by pointing to its safety record, which shows that carrying fuel through pipelines is considerably safer than carrying fuel in tanker trucks or railroad cars.
