 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Shanxi </LOCATION> province has confiscated 2,700 cars from bureaucrats who squandered public money, according to an official report today. The Guangming Daily said the northern province, one of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s poorest, earned $ 13.5 million by reselling the vehicles and fining government departments that illegally purchased the cars last year The money will go to education, boosting the province's education budget by 7.1 percent this year, the newspaper said. New cars have been a main target of a yearlong government campaign to cut waste and reduce public spending. The Communist Party Politburo last month barred all senior party and government leaders from driving imported cars. But the Guangming Daily said local departments in <LOCATION> Shanxi </LOCATION> had ignored government restrictions on buying new vehicles, and that many cars were obtained fraudulently. Some offices used money set aside for natural disasters and education, while others used their cars for personal pleasure and profit, the daily reported. Many of the offices registered their cars in the names of individuals or army units. Offices found violating regulations on buying cars were fined 30 percent to 40 percent of the car's value, the daily said.
