<HEAD>Trial Begins For Parents in Starvation Death of Son</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> WILKES-BARRE </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ The parents of a 14-year-old boy never meant for their oldest child to die, believing throughout a 42-day fast that the Lord would save them from a financial crisis, their attorney said. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> and <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> <PERSON> Cottam </PERSON>, accused of murder in the starving death of their son, <PERSON> Eric </PERSON>, had hoped their faith would sustain them through hard times, defense attorney <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Flora </PERSON> said during opening statements Friday in the Cottams' trial in <LOCATION> Luzerne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> court. <PERSON> Flora </PERSON> said the couple and their 12-year-old daughter, <PERSON> Laura </PERSON>, were shocked when they found <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> dead Jan. 3 at their home in nearby <LOCATION> Nuangola </LOCATION>. `` They never believed anyone would die and they thought God would intervene,'' <PERSON> Flora </PERSON> said. Mrs. <PERSON> Cottam </PERSON> wept quietly throughout the opening arguments, while her husband, a former minister in the Seventh-day <ORGANIZATION> Adventist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, sat stoically beside her. After <PERSON> Eric </PERSON>'s death, his parents and sister were hospitalized for malnutrition. The family went without food for six weeks despite having saved $ 3,775 they said was a tithe belonging to God, police said. The 5-foot-9-inch teen-ager weighed 69 pounds when he died. In other statements, <PERSON> Flora </PERSON> said the Cottams did not seek help because authorities did nothing years earlier when the couple learned their children had been sexually molested. He said they were too scared to turn to outsiders because they were afraid the children would be taken from them and hurt. `` The evidence will show more than anything else they feared the very thing we look to for help,'' <PERSON> Flo