<HEAD>Murder Convictions in Gay Attack Reversed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A state appeals court overturned the murder convictions of three men in an alleged `` gay-bashing,'' ruling that the evidence failed to justify the convictions. The 1st <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that no murderous blows were struck before the victim's head fatally struck the pavement. The court said the man was struck twice _ slapped and probably punched. `` The attack was unprovoked and seems clearly to have been motivated solely by -LRB- the three men's -RRB- mindless homophobia,'' said Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Newsom </PERSON> in the appeals court's 2-1 ruling. The court cited the legal standard for murder when no intent to kill is shown: acting deliberately, and in disregard for human life, a person must commit an act that is inherently life-threatening. That standard can not be met by a beating unless it is `` so brutal that death is a probable consequence,'' said <PERSON> Newsom </PERSON>. The court ordered the convictions reduced to involuntary manslaughter _ a death resulting from an ordinary assault _ with a maximum sentence of four years. If upheld, the ruling would reduce the men's convictions from second-degree murder to involuntary manslaughter. Lawyers for two of the men said they would be eligible for immediate release from prison, where they have been since 1984 on sentences of 15 years to life. `` Any anti-gay behavior is despicable, and people should be prosecuted to the fullest extent of the law,'' said <PERSON> Maureen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kallins </PERSON>, lawyer for defendant <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>. `` But this was never a murder. ... <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> slapped someone and a slap does not make him a murderer.'' Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> said there was a good chance the state would appeal the ruling. He said it was `` a close question'' whether the men's actions were life-threatening, a requirement for a murder conviction, but that the appeals court should have let the jury resolve the issue. White, then 22, and co-defendants <PERSON> Donny </PERSON> <PERSON> Clanton </PERSON>, 19, and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, 19, had driven 40 miles to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> from their homes in <LOCATION> Vallejo </LOCATION>. A witness quoted <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> as saying, `` Let's go beat up some faggots.'' The men went to an area of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> frequented by homosexuals and pursued two passers-by. One, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connell </PERSON>, 41, was struck and knocked to the sidewalk; he went into a coma and died days later. The court said the cause of death was the impact of his head on the pavement. The killing, and several other assaults to which the men pleaded guilty, prompted a public outcry. Then Mayor <PERSON> Dianne </PERSON> <PERSON> Feinstein </PERSON> posted a $ 10,000 reward in the case, and a state law was passed increasing damages in suits by victims of `` gay-bashing.''
