he Sept. 6 parliamentary elections. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 28 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. Police Commissioner Gen. <PERSON> Hennie </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Witt </PERSON> on Friday imposed restrictions on the two-day meeting of the anti-apartheid labor groups, allowing only union members to attend, prohibiting political banners and limiting discussions to labor issues. Dozens of police were present when labor officials began arriving this morning. The two organizations are the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Trade Unions, which has more than 900,000 members, and the smaller <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unions </ORGANIZATION>. As part of a defiance campaign led in part by the trade union group, dozens of blacks successfully sought treatment Friday at a whites-only hospital wing in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and clergymen announced plans to defy bus segregation laws in the capital city, <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>. Similar protests took place at six whites-only hospitals on Aug. 2. On Friday, police fired birdshot to break up a protest at <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s Plain township, wounding three mixed-race high school students. Another police contingent set up roadblocks outside the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cape </ORGANIZATION> and fired tear gas at mixed-race and black students who had erected barricades on the campus. Police officials said two officers were wounded by a gunman in <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s Plain, and reported that two black men were killed by rioters in separate incidents elsewhere after their vehicles were attacked, one by people hurling stones and one by a firebomb. In <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, a group of black and white clergymen announced that a campaign to desegregate the city's transit system will begin Monday. The ministers said blacks would board whites-only buses and whites would ride in mini-bus taxis, which are supposed to carry only blacks. They said the weeklong campaign would be peaceful and invited Pretoria-based foreign diplomats to observe.
