ON> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and stored the drug inside legitimate shipments of furniture. In one case the cocaine, in liquid form, was hidden inside plastic bags and put into a fish tank. `` It was discovered when the fish died,'' an administration source said, adding that in another incident the drug was neatly and professionally stuffed inside the planks of imported picnic tables. The distribution chain starts with the large drug cartels in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and then moves to Colombian dealers inside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. From there it goes in quantities of up to 150 pounds to the `` trafficking groups,'' mostly Jamaicans, Dominicans and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> street gangs, <PERSON> Gutensohn </PERSON> said. `` They purchase smaller levels and bring it to the inner cities,'' he said. The trafficking groups sell several pounds to dealers who operate what are called `` crack houses.'' Then the `` crack house'' owners sell to individual users. `` You've got level after level,'' <PERSON> Gutensohn </PERSON> said. Colombian cocaine made a notable entrance on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> streets in the 1970s and trafficking has grown to the point where `` Cocaine and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> are essentially the same thing,'' said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, spokesman for the administration's Office of National Drug Control Policy. `` But, hypothetically if you've locked up a dozen or so people that would not break the trade,'' he said. A <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official who deals with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> drug issues said: `` I think they are moving the networks out of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, living there and enjoying the wealth, but the cocaine's going out from God knows where.'' A sustained crackdown in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> could `` over a long time have an impact, but I do n't think you could possibly tell for a year, and even if you grab the bosses, there's going to be somebody else who takes over,'' said the official, who following department guidelines spoke on condition he not be further identified. <PERSON> Kennington </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a private research group seeking alternative strategies for fighting the drug war, also said cocaine traffickers would move their operation bases to safer areas. `` If you push it down in one place, it will pop up in another,'' he said.
