<HEAD>NASA: Photos Show Southern Lights On Neptune, Nitrogen In Triton
Atmosphere</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with evidence of broad dust bands
around planet. Picks up 6th grafs pvs, `Evidence for...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Voyager 2, discovered broad, flat bands of dust orbiting <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION> and found evidence the planet has `` southern lights,'' <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> said today. The probe also detected nitrogen in the atmosphere of <ORGANIZATION> Triton </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION> whose pink snow and ice volcanoes were described by excited scientists as unique in the solar system, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> said. `` There's dust bands _ they're broad,'' said <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> astronomer <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Terrile </PERSON>, describing the findings from latest photorgraphs. The bands orbit <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION>'s equator, as do its narrow rings that were discovered by <PERSON> Voyager </PERSON> earlier. Although Voyager has passed its closest encounters with <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Triton </ORGANIZATION>, it continued today to back recorded photographs taken during the time of closest approach. And scientists and engineers celebrated the spacecraft's successful flyby. `` My understanding was most of the engineers and science team had one hell of a party last night,'' <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON>, a Voyager engineer, said today. The one-ton space probe capped its historic 4.43-billion-mile, 12-year tour of four planets when it skimmed 3,048 miles over <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION>'s north pole Thursday night, then dove past <ORGANIZATION> Triton </ORGANIZATION>, the planet's largest moon. It made its closest approach about 23,900 miles above the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION>'s surface at 2:10 a.m. PDT Friday. During its approach to <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Voyager </PERSON> discovered six moons besides <ORGANIZATION> Triton </ORGANIZATION> and Nereid, which were first observed from Earth. It also discovered one complete ring of debris around the planet and a partial ring, or ring arc, scientists believe will also prove to be a complete ring. While only the narrow rings were visible as <PERSON> Voyager </PERSON> flew toward <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION>, the broad dust bands became visible when they were backlit by sunlight after the space probe passed the planet, <PERSON> Terrile </PERSON> said. That makes them look like <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION>'s broad rings, but only when viewed from behind <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION>. The same thing happened when <PERSON> Voyager </PERSON> passed Uranus in 1986. That planet had 10 narrow rings when seen by the approaching spacecraft, which then found extensive bands of dust after passing Uranus. <PERSON> Terrile </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION>'s dust bands are not as extensive. Evidence for the glowing lights, known as an aurora, was found at 30 degrees south latitude on <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION> as <PERSON> Voyager </PERSON>'s ultraviolet light sensor made a north-to-south scan of the planet, deputy project scientist <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> <PERSON> Miner </PERSON> said today. Because the scan did n't cover different longitudes, scientists do n't know the aurora's full extent, or whether it circles <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION> east to west, as do <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>'s auroras, <PERSON> Miner </PERSON> said. Miner said <PERSON> Voyager </PERSON> also found nitrogen in <ORGANIZATION> Triton </ORGANIZATION>'s atmosphere. Nitrogen makes up 78 percent of Earth's atmosphere. On Earth, the northern and southern lights encircle the poles, but can get pushed closer to the equator when the sun generates magnetic storms. However, it would be very unusual for an aurora on Earth to get as close to the equator as 30 degrees latitude. Auroras are caused when electrically charged particles in the solar wind spiral in toward a planet along magnetivc field lines. On Earth they glow in visible light. <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION>'s lights glow ultraviolet because of hydrogen in its atmosphere. Engineers spent the night unloading Voyager's eight-track tape recorder _ playing back pictures and scientific data recorded during the <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Triton </ORGANIZATION> rendezvous _ and also loaded new instructions telling the probe how to point its cameras and sensors, Urban said. Voyager today started sending back its most detailed images of <ORGANIZATION> Triton </ORGANIZATION>, which is four-fifth's the size of <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>'s moon. But pictures returned Friday were more than enough to stun scientists. `` The range of geological forms is dazzling,'' astronomer-author <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sagan </PERSON> said Friday. `` We are almost certainly in a regime of volcanism involving ices, maybe exotic ices'' such as water ice mixed with frozen nitrogen or methane -LRB- natural gas -RRB-. The photographs show a cracked, frozen <ORGANIZATION> Triton </ORGANIZATION> scarred by thousand-foot-high ridges, fault lines, bowl-shaped craters, mysterious domes and dark spots ringed with white halos that so far defy explanation. `` The images returned this morning revealed a world unlike any we've ever seen,'' Voyager project scientist <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> said Friday at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s Jet Propulsion Laboratory. Icy volcanic flows have been seen on Uranus' moon Ariel and some other moons, but <ORGANIZATION> Triton </ORGANIZATION> is the first place scientists have actually seen ice volcanoes, <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> said. Photographs showed at least three inactive volcanoes. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> geologist <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyce </PERSON> said one of the ice volcanoes _ which look like dry lakebeds filled with smooth material _ measures several hundred miles across. Some were encircled with cliffs 1,000 to 2,000 feet high. The properties of exotic ices of water, methane and nitrogen `` are very different from ordinary ice,'' said <PERSON> Sagan </PERSON>, a member of the Voyager imaging team. `` That may explain the exoticness of the landforms.'' Parts of the moon are frozen methane discolored by a bombardment of radiation that produced chemical changes, <PERSON> Sagan </PERSON> said. `` We've got pink snow. Think about how exotic that is.'' Preliminary measurements of <ORGANIZATION> Triton </ORGANIZATION>'s magnetic field suggest that it does not have a north pole and a south pole like <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>'s magnetic field, but rather multiple poles, researchers said. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Strom </PERSON> of the Voyager imaging team said the relative scarcity of craters on <ORGANIZATION> Triton </ORGANIZATION> tends to confirm speculation that <ORGANIZATION> Triton </ORGANIZATION> originated outside the solar system and became captured by <PERSON> Neptune </PERSON>'s gravity, perhaps after colliding with one of its moons. <PERSON> Voyager </PERSON> also revealed that <ORGANIZATION> Triton </ORGANIZATION> has an atmosphere and is covered with a haze of what could be photochemical smog. On the moon's sunlit southern hemisphere, frozen methane or other volatile material is boiling off the surface, causing haze, and condensing on the moon's cooler regions, scientists said. Voyager 2 was launched in 1977 and explored Jupiter in 1979, <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> in 1981 and Uranus in 1986. Until Oct. 2, Voyager 2 will look back at <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION>. Then it will head toward interstellar space. Weary <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> scientists, many of whom spent all night at the laboratory analyzing data returning from the spacecraft, gushed over the spectacular images being received. <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Soderblom </PERSON> of the Voyager imaging team said: `` Wow! What a way to leave the solar system.''
