<HEAD>Pope Criticizes Communism, Lauds Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> on Saturday marked the 50th anniversary of the outbreak of World War II by condemning Nazism and Marxism as `` substitute religions'' and hailing democratic reform in his native <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. The pontiff singled out <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> while expressing support for the right of people to determine their own governments. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> last week installed the first non-Communist government leader in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bloc </LOCATION>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> made his appeals in a 20-page apostolic letter marking the Sept. 1 anniversary of the start of the war and a 12-page message to Polish bishops on the same subject. In the official English translation of the letter, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said in it was `` our duty before God'' to remember the war in order to honor its victims, forgive the offenses committed, and reflect on its causes. `` We have a duty to learn from the past so that never again will there arise a set of factors capable of triggering a similar conflagration,'' he said in the apostolic letter, according to an official English-language text. He traced <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> atrocities to its denial of God and law, which he said led to the crushing of human rights and eventually the rights of nations. `` Nazi paganism and Marxist dogma are both basically totalitarian ideologies and tend to become substitute religions,'' he wrote in one of his harshest condemnations yet of communism. Focusing on his native land, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> was on the winning side of the war but that under <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> rule, Poles `` were forced to ask themselves whether they in fact being treated as the vanquished'' and were compelled `` to undertake new struggles. `` For in truth, a state whose society is not sovereign is no sovereign state at all,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said in the message to Polish bishops. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> was apparently referring to the campaign of the Solidarity labor movement that culminated last week with the appointment of a non-Communist as prime minister. At a news conference to release the papal documents, Cardinal <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Etchegaray </PERSON> said the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> was holding up <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> as an example. `` He knows very well that the Polish experience is n't limited to a national reality but can also be applied to other situations, above all in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' said the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> cardinal, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> and Peace. But asked whether the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> was advocating democracy for <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the Baltic states, <PERSON> Etchegaray </PERSON> said, `` One should not imagine that the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> tries to revise pacts, to revise <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s borders. In his statements, the pope also made a special appeal for an end to discrimination. He singled out the Nazi slaughter of the Jews as something `` which will forever remain a shame for humanity.'' About 6 million Jews were killed in the Holocaust. Jews and Catholics are now embroiled in a dispute over a Catholic convent at the site of the <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> death camp in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Jewish groups are outraged at the Polish church's refusal to move the convent as promised. They say the convent and its Christian symbols are insults to the memory of the 2.5 million Jews who died there. Asked why the pope had not intervened, <PERSON> Etchegaray </PERSON> said: `` Knowing the degree to which the pope respects the local churches ... the pope shows himself even more respectful of the local church he comes from.''
