<HEAD>At Least 36 Killed in Sinhalese Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At least 20 people were shot and killed in a central Sri Lankan village, military officals said Saturday, and residents accused soldiers of carrying out the killings. Up to 16 more people were killed in various attacks during the past 24 hours, officials said. All the victims of Friday's attack in <LOCATION> Tirapanne </LOCATION>, 100 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, were Sinhalese and their bodies were thrown in six houses that were later burned, said military officials, who can not be identified under briefing rules. Residents in <LOCATION> Anuradhapura </LOCATION>, 12 miles from <LOCATION> Tirapanne </LOCATION>, blamed the attack on soldiers in civilian clothes and said they apparently meant to avenge the slayings of a fellow soldier's parents. The residents, contacted by telephone, spoke on condition of anonymity. Pro-government vigilante groups and the military have been accused in the past of killing civilians during operations against Sinhalese extremists. The government denies the charge. An opposition lawmaker, <PERSON> Janak </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahendra </PERSON> <PERSON> Adikari </PERSON>, said in <LOCATION> Anuradhapura </LOCATION> that the Tirapanne toll could be much higher. He said hundreds of villagers had fled to <LOCATION> Anuradhapura </LOCATION>. In another attack Friday, men in military uniforms burned six or seven homes in <LOCATION> Katukeliyawa </LOCATION>, 15 miles south of <LOCATION> Anuradhapura </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Adikari </PERSON>, contacted by telephone. `` There are reports of five to six civilian casualties in this attack, but we do not have confirmation,'' he said. The military could not immediately confirm the attack. The government armed the military with sweeping powers under emergency laws to curb an anti-government campaign by the Sinhalese extremists belonging to the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. The front stepped up its campaign of assassinations and strikes after President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> imposed a nationwide state of emergency June 20. The government says at least 1,000 people have died since July 15. In their latest attack, radicals detonated a bomb under a police vehicle in <LOCATION> Kurunegala </LOCATION> district Friday, killing three policemen and a civilian driver, the military officials said. One laborer traveling in the vehicle also was killed and five policemen were injured in the blast about 85 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, the officials said. They said two policemen and a wildlife official were killed Friday in an ambush of their vehicle in <LOCATION> Anuradhapur </LOCATION> district, which carries the same name as its largest town. A naval officer, a front member and three civilians were killed in separate incidents during the past 24 hours in southern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, the officials said. One unidentified body also was found they said. At least 5,000 people have died in the Sinhalese extremist campaign, launched in July, 1987 to protest the government's peace overtures to Tamil separatists in the northeast. The radicals said the government gave too many concessions to the minority Tamil community in an India-sponsored peace plan of June 29, 1987, that aimed to end the six-year Tamil demand for an independent nation. Sinhalese radicals also were angered by the deployment of <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> peacekeeping soldiers in the northeast, invited to enforce the June, 1987, accord. They said the Indian presence compromised the country's sovereignty. The accord collapsed when the strongest Tamil rebel group rejected it, and began attacking Indian troops. At least 1,000 Indian soldiers have died in the fighting. More than 10,000 Sri Lankans have been killed in the six-year separatist war. Tamils, who form 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people, allege discrimination in jobs and education by the Sinhalese majority who make up 75 percent of the population. The Sinhalese control the government and the military. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> became involved in the ethnic problems of its small southeastern neighbor because of the sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils.
