<HEAD>New Lutheran Church Assures Recognition Of Dissent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `Bishop Green...', to CORRECT first name to
Glenn, sted Green, add location of synod.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has decided to make sure dissenting voices are heard when the new denomination makes a pronouncement on a controversial social issue. The church approved a policy of recognizing substantial minority views Friday in a session that also affirmed membership in the sometimes controversial <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> of Churches. The ecumenical organizations include most major <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> and Eastern Orthodox churches in this country and around the world. The method of handling church pronouncements, including dissent, came in the adoption of a document detailing the basis for speaking out on moral issues in society. Delegates narrowly approved an amendment offered by <PERSON> Christa </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> of <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, providing that whenever significant division is shown in approving social pronouncements, summaries will be given of dissenting positions. The Rev. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lay </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, argued this would `` reduce the force'' of statements and the Rev. <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Knudson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Milwaukie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, contended it would `` take away impact and meaning.'' However, the Rev. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Spring </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said `` intelligent and moral honesty'' demanded that there be room in the church for those who differ and that this should be openly recognized. `` As a parish pastor, this is one of the problems I have struggled with when a stand is taken with which someone does n't agree,'' he said The provision was approved by a 489-453 vote. Lengthy debate preceded the vote for membership of the 5.3-million denomination, fourth-largest among <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Protestants, in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>. The council has been involved in leadership conflicts and financial strains and is undergoing structural reforms. Bishop <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Nycklemoe </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Southeastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Synod </LOCATION>, based in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, said he had reversed his opposition to belonging to the council, sensing `` new directions and new spirit'' in it. Of the three Lutheran bodies merged into the denomination, the former <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> had belonged to the national council, but not the former <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> or former <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> Lutheran Churches. The eight-day assembly, which runs through next Wednesday, also adopted working guidelines for ecumenical efforts for <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> unity. Citing the biblical and theological bases for it, the 5,000-word document urges work for `` the oneness to which God calls the world in the saving gift of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>. `` It also means to recognize the brokenness of the church in history and the call of God, especially in this century, to heal this disunity of Christ's people.''
