<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> on Saturday to discuss coordinating economic aid for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and keeping international attention focused on peace efforts in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. `` President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> expressed his concern about the general situation in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and reiterated <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for efforts by the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> to resolve the issue,'' according to a statement issued by the vacation White House. A fleet of French warships remained off <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> for a possible evacuation of <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> citizens. `` The two presidents commented on the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- cease-fire in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and agreed to keep the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spotlight on the problem.'' On the subject of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, the statement said that the two presidents discussed the election last week of Solidarity activist <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> as <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s prime minister `` and agreed to continue offering the support of their two goverments.'' `` Both presidents want to encourage the new government, while keeping in mind the delicacy of the situation,'' the statement said. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has promised <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> $ 119 million in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic aid and is supporting some $ 325 million in new loans from international lending agencies. The White House statement, quoting <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> directly, said he told <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, `` We want to help <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in a coordinated way. They need an effective reform program that takes on the economic realities they face.'' Vacationing here through Labor Day, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also entertained evangelist <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> on Saturday. The president started the day pursuing one of his favorite vacation activities, ocean fishing. He took out his speed boat <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION> in hopes of succeeding where he has so far failed on his 10 days in this coastal resort town. Earlier, he played tennis at his home on <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>'s Point. Evening plans called for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> to entertain some 35 relatives who live in the <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION> area. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s son <PERSON> Jeb </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and his wife and children also were visiting. By Saturday, the president had yet to catch a fish despite daily excursions onto the water. On Friday his <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> body guards agreed to keep their protective boats and the media chase boats further away so as not to scare away a prospective catch. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> and his wife were the latest in a stream of guests at Walker's Point since <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s arrival Aug. 16. The Grahams and Bushes were expected to attend church services together Sunday. All of the president's five children and their families have been on hand for several days. The Bushes this past week entertained Danish Prime Minister <PERSON> Poul </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> for an overnight visit. In addition, several friends have joined the president for golf, dinner and tennis. Canadian Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> is scheduled to arrive here Wednesday for what is billed as a personal, social occasion rather than a working visit. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been receiving daily intelligence briefings while on vacation and has conducted routine business, but mostly spends his time at golf, tennis, running and boating.
