<HEAD>10-Year-Old Boy Moves Toward Adult Homicide Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WLK1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STROUDSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The defendant wriggled in his chair, hiking his elbows onto the armrests. He crossed his arms when he stood before the judge, who called him Mr. <PERSON> Kocher </PERSON> and told him he had been charged with shooting a 7-year-old girl in the back with a hunting rifle. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> <PERSON> Kocher </PERSON> pleaded innocent, moving closer to becoming apparently the youngest person ever in the country to be tried on an adult homicide charge. He is 10. The boy let out a heavy sigh as he turned to his parents, <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Kocher </PERSON>, after his arraignment ended Friday. Prosecutors have ruled out the death penalty if the the fourth-grader is convicted. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Pazuhanich </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Monroe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> assistant district attorney, said life in prison remains a possibility, though he has n't decided yet what punishment he would seek. No trial date has been set. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON>'s lawyer said prosecutors, who fought a request to move the case to juvenile court, should realize they are not dealing with `` a miniature adult.'' `` He does n't understand the concept of murder and does n't fully understand the concept of death,'' <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansford </PERSON> said after the arraignment. `` I do n't know how to prepare him.'' <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> is charged with killing a playmate, first-grader <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON> <PERSON> Carr </PERSON>. She died March 6, two months before <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON>'s 10th birthday, after she was shot as she rode on the back of a snowmobile. Schools were closed that day because of heavy snow. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON>, 13-year-old <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratti </PERSON> and other children were spending the day playing video games at <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>'s house in <LOCATION> Kresgeville </LOCATION>, a town of 250 people in the foothills of the <LOCATION> Pocono </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>. After <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>'s father, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratti </PERSON>, found dirty dishes in the house, he put the video games off limits, and the children went outside to ride snowmobiles. But <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON>'s parents had told him not to ride snowmobiles when they were n't around, and he left the house angry and went to his home next door, <PERSON> Ratti </PERSON> testified. The boy said the shooting was an accident while he was playing with a gun. But investigators gave this account of what happened next, ticking off a list of deliberate steps that the judge cited in his decision to have the boy tried as an adult: <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> took a key from under a lamp in his parents' bedroom and opened his father's gun cabinet, took out a .35 - caliber <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> lever-action hunting rifle his father had taught him to shoot, and loaded After unlocking a bedroom window and opening it, <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> took out the screen and set it aside, and he pointed the rifle out the window, investigators said. At 1:05 p.m. a shot rang out, and <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON>, about 100 yards away, fell from the back of the snowmobile <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> was driving. The rifle's recoil slammed the scope into <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON>'s face, cutting his forehead. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> put the rifle back in the cabinet, bandaged his forehead and hid a spent shell casing. Fearing a sniper was on the loose, <PERSON> Ratti </PERSON> called <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> and told him to come back to his house for safety. <PERSON> Ratti </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Trudy </PERSON>, testified that <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> explained the bandage on his forehead by saying he cut himself with a knife when a dog jumped on him as he made a peanut butter-and-jelly sandwich. As others frantically tried to help <PERSON> Jessica </PERSON>, <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> sat on the Rattis' floor and resumed playing the video game, <PERSON> Ratti </PERSON> testified. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> kept playing the game while the other children prayed and made get-well cards for the girl. `` If you do n't think about it, you wo n't be sad,'' <PERSON> Ratti </PERSON> quoted <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> as saying. The girl was pronounced dead about an hour after she was shot. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> was arrested two days later after investigators found his blood on the rifle. <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> told psychotherapists he was playing `` hunter'' when he was looking through the gun's scope and the rifle accidentally fired. He said he could n't see anything through the scope but snow and trees, Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadoff </PERSON>, a psychiatrist who examined <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> for the court, has testified. A ballistics specialist testified the rifle could not have discharged accidently unless a severe blow to the rifle forced the hammer to strike the firing pin. Citing <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON>'s apparent mental stability, above-average grades and the deliberate actions he allegedly took before and after the shooting, <LOCATION> Monroe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Judge <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Vican </PERSON> in June refused to move the case from criminal court to juvenile court. <PERSON> Hansford </PERSON> has appealed. <PERSON> Pazuhanich </PERSON> said the case, one of two murders in the county this year, troubles him. `` I'm preoccupied with how the boy is reacting to the process. I'm preoccupied by the tension that's in that neighborhood when you have the Rattis and the Kochers living side by side and the <ORGANIZATION> Carrs </ORGANIZATION> still visit the Rattis and everybody is in close proximity to one another,'' he said. `` You wonder, as I'm sure the <ORGANIZATION> Carrs </ORGANIZATION> do, what was going through his head and what to do.''
