<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of civil rights demonstrators, men clad in black, women and children in white, marched quietly upon the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and the Capitol today in a reprise of the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>'s historic `` Silent March'' of 1917 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> The <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> march was `` concerned with one issue alone _ the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and its recent hostile decisions'' diluting affirmative action and minority set-aside programs, said <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooks </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>. But the tone and style of the protest, led by six drummers with muffled drums, was fashioned after a march in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> 72 years ago to protest segregation and the lynchings of blacks in the South. On that occasion, W.E.B. <PERSON> DuBois </PERSON> led 8,000 people down Fifth Avenue in utter silence; that day, too, the men dressed in black and the women and children in white. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> estimated the turnout when the march began at only 5,000, but revised that figure to 35,000 as the ranks swelled during the 1 -LCB- hour procession to the Capitol from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s Mall. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capitol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> put the crowd which assembled on the Capitol grounds at the end of the march at 18,500, according Officer <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Nevitt </PERSON>. Hooks claimed from the podium that the march had drawn a turnout of 135,000. Each of the marchers carried a printed affirmation which said: `` We march to send a message to all people regardless of race, color, religion, sex or ethnic orgin, that we will not and can not acquiesce quietly as an uncaring <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> majority dismantles court ruling after court ruling and turns its face toward the dark past and away from the present and future.'' And, it said, `` we march proudly in the footsteps of our brave sisters and brothers from another age who marched 72 years ago in silent witness against lynching, discrimination, segregation and racism. For us not to march at this point in time would be a grave disservice to them.'' The protest was aimed specifically at four decisions by the court this year. In the view of civil rights lawyers, the ruling in <ORGANIZATION> Patterson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> vs. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McLean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> sharply limited the previous power of minorities to sue private parties, including schools, for discrimatory practices. Similarly, the court's decision in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> vs. J. <ORGANIZATION> A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Croson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was seen as diluting job set-aside programs and other affirmative action plans. March organizers also assailed the decision in <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wilks </PERSON>, which allowed white firefighters in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, to attack a consent decree calling for the promotion of blacks as a case of `` reverse discrimination.'' The fourth ruling, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s Cove vs. <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON>, was criticized as shifting the entire burden of proof in job discrimination cases to the victims of employer bias, rather than requiring employers to demonstrate, at the same time, that their hiring practices furthered legitimate business interests. The march culminated with a rally at the Capitol, where Hooks and other civil rights leaders were scheduled to speak. The Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, the Rev. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, and mayors <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmoke </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> also were on the program. On Friday, Hooks talked about recent incidents of violence directed at his organization, saying they have `` raised our level of concern not only for ourselves but for all other institutions and individuals who traditionally draw the wrath of racists.'' Several shots were fired July 19 into the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. Last Monday, a tear-gas bomb, concealed in a package sent through the mail, exploded at a regional office in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. `` These are the acts of terrorists,'' Hooks said. `` People could have been behind those lighted windows in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, and in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> several innocent people, including children and the elderly, had to receive medical care.'' `` If these acts ... were meant to frighten us or deter us from any course of action, they failed completely. We did not give in to terrorism when the <PERSON> Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> <PERSON> Klan </PERSON> was riding high and mighty and we will not give in to these latter-day terrorists,'' he said. `` We are not looking toward bringing vast numbers of people to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Hooks </PERSON> said. `` In this instance, the medium is the message and the medium is the silent march.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has often been the target of major demonstrations in the capital in recent years. An estimated 325,000 turned out last spring to urge the court to stand by its 1973 decision legalizing abortion. However, the court weeks later softened that ruling in a case seen as a victory for anti-abortion forces.
