<HEAD>Army Studies Seized Drug Records, Eight Arrests In Candidate Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Army officials pored over seized records from a drug baron's financial empire Saturday and police announced the arrest of eight more suspects in the killing of a presidential candidate. Army Gen. <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Niebles </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview he expected the seized records `` to be of great value in our campaign'' to wipe out narcotics trafficking. Authorities said the records include numbers of local and foreign bank transactions as well as names of lawyers and others involved in the financial empire of reputed cocaine kingpin <PERSON> Gonzalo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Gacha </PERSON>. The records were discovered at his rural, bunker-like estate seized by the army Thursday near the town of <LOCATION> Pacho </LOCATION>, about 60 miles north of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. `` We are processing these documents, which provide fine information on the estate,'' said <PERSON> Niebles </PERSON>, commander of the 13th army brigade. He declined to disclose details of the records or anticipate what actions, such as future raids, they might inspire. According to the <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tiempo </ORGANIZATION>, the records represent the financial books for <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Gacha </PERSON> since 1982. <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Gacha </PERSON> _ nicknamed `` The Mexican'' for his affection for that country's music and culture _ is among the bosses of the so-called <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> cartel. Based in the industrial city of <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION>, the cartel is the world's largest cocaine-trafficking organization and supplies an estimated 80 percent of the cocaine distributed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Dozens of luxurious homes, apartments and offices believed owned by <PERSON> Gacha </PERSON> were among hundreds of properties siezed in an eight-day-old offensive by police and military forces nationwide. The unprecendented crackdown was prompted by the assassination of a highly popular presidential candidate, Sen. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Galan </PERSON>. Police in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> announced the arrest of eight more suspects in <PERSON> Galan </PERSON>'s killing Aug. 16 at a political rally on <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>'s southern outskirts, bringing to 13 the total of suspected participants or accomplices under arrest. Five heavily armed men were arrested in a surprise raid last week at a downtown <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> apartment. Four of them were identified by more than a dozen witnesses at the rally. <PERSON> Galan </PERSON>'s killing capped a 48-hour wave of assassinations, including that of a national police colonel in <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> and a prominent <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> magistrate. It outraged Colombian society and inspired the government crackdown, backed by a series of tough emergency decrees by President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>. Barco renewed extradition with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and streamlined the procedure to reduce the need for extensive judicial review. Under bloody intimidation by traffickers, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> nullified the extradition treaty in June 1987. About 11,000 people have been detained in the government sweep, including a handful of suspects described by Colombian authorities as major traffickers or drug-money managers wanted by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Drug and legal experts at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy were working over the weekend to try to arrange the extradition of some of the suspects, sources said, as were Colombian justice officials. On Friday, authorities disclosed the arrest in <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> of <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Gacha </PERSON>'s alleged finance chief, <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Galeano </PERSON> <PERSON> Berrio </PERSON>. Army officials said he was wanted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on drug charges. They said they also arrested <PERSON> Freddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, a son of <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Gacha </PERSON>, and that he also is wanted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but there was no immediate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> confirmation. American narcotics experts in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> previously have confirmed that three other suspects arrested in the sweep are wanted by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts. Cartel bosses such as <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Gacha </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Escobar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Ochoa </PERSON> continue to elude authorities. According to the <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Espectador </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Gacha </PERSON> escaped to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> Wednesday in a private aircraft. Local press reports have placed <PERSON> Escobar </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> cartel's most notorious leader, in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. The raids on drug estates have revealed a penchant for the luxurious, the kinky and the macabre. At one ranch owned by <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Gacha </PERSON> soldiers found a wooden gallows, but said they have no idea if it was ever used. Another drug lord's estate featured a two-story stone playhouse for children built like a medieval castle. Opulent, mirrored bedrooms with tiger skins, valuable paintings and other works of art, saunas and indoor swimming pools are common features. At a mansion outside <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> believed to belong to reputed trafficker <PERSON> Camilo </PERSON> <PERSON> Zapata </PERSON>, the army uncovered a room filled with articles of withcraft, including potions, dried tigers' feet, rotting vegetables and fruit and images of Christ immersed in alcohol.
