<SECOND>AM-Afghan-Jalalabad,0847</SECOND>
<HEAD>War-Torn Jalalabad Struggles To Recover</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE: <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> has been under siege ever since Soviet troops withdrew early this year. The pressure from guerrillas has eased somewhat, but <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> remains a city on edge. An <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> reporter visited <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> last week.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JALALABAD, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As this city tries to return to normalcy after six months on the front line of the Afghan war, the frequent boom of heavy weapons serves as a reminder that guerrillas are still around. Schools, shops and factories are open again, but <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> is a shadow of the legendary garden city beloved by Afghan kings for its <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> climate and leisurely lifestyle. This strategic city on the road from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is shell-pocked, but officials say the worst is over and there is widespread longing for peace. Since Soviet troops withdrew from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on Feb. 15, <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> has been the main battleground for the Soviet-backed government and U.S.-backed guerrillas trying to topple it and set up an interim government in the city. The rebels failed to take <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, 45 miles from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, after nearly 10 weeks of the most intense bombardment of the war in April and May. Government troops then pushed the guerrillas back along the main highway that leads to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, beyond the strategic crossroads of <LOCATION> Samarkhel </LOCATION>. Local officials took reporters to <LOCATION> Samarkhel </LOCATION>, nine miles southeast of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, which government forces captured from the guerrillas in mid-June. It had been the most significant gain of the rebels, who call themselves mujahedeen or Islamic Holy Warriors. There were no sounds of gunfire in <LOCATION> Samarkhel </LOCATION>, and government soldiers lounged under the few trees seeking shelter from the noon-day sun and smoking an occasional cigarette. On the yellow, shell-pocked wall of a building once used as a transport office were scrawled the words: `` Interim government of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The hero mujahedeen of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.'' An arch over the road said: `` Long live the Afghan-Soviet friendship.'' Government officials refused to show reporters the Samarkhel garrison, at the foot of a rocky ridge about 2 -LCB- miles away, for what they said were strategic reasons. Although the government claims its troops occupy the garrison, the guerrillas claim it is a no-man's land The ridge itself is the last natural line of defense preventing the government from moving on the main guerrilla areas nearer to the Pakistani border. Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Manok </PERSON> <PERSON> Mangall </PERSON>, governor of <LOCATION> Nangarhar </LOCATION> province which includes <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, said `` the important and significant spots'' were in government hands. But Western reporters on the trip said they had climbed the ridge recently with the guerrillas who controlled it. The guerrillas say controlling this ridge will enable them to launch a successful offensive against the Samarkhel-based government troops once they restock their weapons and ammunition supplies. The loss of <LOCATION> Samarkhel </LOCATION> has made it infinitely more difficult for the guerrillas to accurately launch their main short-range missiles against <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> and its airport. In recent weeks, the airport's gravel runway has been repaired, and reporters flew to <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> on a fixed-wing Antonov 32 rather than by helicopter. But the flight was at night, in complete blackout to minimize risks of a mujahedeen attack. <PERSON> Mangall </PERSON>, who is chairman of the Afghan <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, said there were 12,000 armed guerrillas in <LOCATION> Nangarhar </LOCATION> now, but two-thirds were not fighting. `` Every night, I am negotiating with two or three -LRB- guerrilla -RRB- commanders,'' he said. `` Most of them are tired of war.'' The highly decorated general said the guerrillas have given up their plan to transfer their interim government to <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, `` and the reconstruction of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> is accelerating.'' At <ORGANIZATION> Bayazid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roshan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Nangarhar </LOCATION> teacher's training institute, which reopened last month after a three-month break, classes were very small and many classrooms were empty. A small nucleus of shops have reopened, but in the crowded marketplace, three out of four shops remained shuttered, a sign of continuing uncertainty about the future. The sounds of outgoing artillery fire and missiles and even a few incoming rockets are largely ignored. But the effects of the 840,000 rockets and other heavy artillery which <PERSON> Mangall </PERSON> said had hit <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> during 42 days at the height of the siege are not forgotten. During a brief shopping tour in the bazaar, 22-year-old <PERSON> Takar </PERSON>, who lost three members of his family in rocket attacks five months ago, heard there was an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> journalist around and stopped his bicycle to say: `` I hate the American government because they are assisting opposition groups in our city. They are killing our people. We want peace to come to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.'' At the teacher's training school, 18-year-old <PERSON> Adilla </PERSON> <PERSON> Dehquanzadeh </PERSON> said she wanted to ask President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> why the Americans are arming the mujahedeen. `` If I met him, I would ask him not to equip the opposition with new weapons, not to kill our innocent people, especially our children, and to support national reconciliation,'' she said.
