<HEAD>Police Say Fighting Diminishing After Soviet Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Christian and Syrian forces battled with rockets and artillery on Saturday, but a police spokesman said hostilities have diminished since a Soviet envoy began a peace mission in the ravaged country. The spokesman, who can not be named in line with standing rules, said two people were killed and nine wounded in the clashes. Scores of shells and rockets crashed in residential neighborhoods on both sides of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s dividing Green Line. The new casualties brought the overal toll to 796 killed and 2,231 wounded since fighting broke out March 8 between the traditionally pro-Western Christians and Syrian troops. The spokesman noted that the exchanges were `` limited to two areas, which reflects the noticeable decrease in the intensity and scope of the shelling duels'' since Soviet envoy <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarasov </PERSON> began his mission on Wednesday. It was <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s first direct mediation in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> since the civil war broke out in April 1975. <PERSON> Tarasov </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s chief <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> ally, where he met with Foreign Minister <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Sharaa </PERSON> on Wednesday. He drove to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> Thursday and met for two days with Moslem and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> leaders, including Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, commander of <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> army units with whom <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> has refused to negotiate a peace settlement. <PERSON> Tarasov </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, returned to <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> on Friday and was expected to fly home this weekend for consultations with Kremlin leaders. His mission coincided with a French naval buildup off <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> said it sent a six-ship flotilla to the Eastern Mediterranean on a `` humanitarian mission'' to evacuate 7,000 French nationals if the situation worsens. But <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s Moslem allies and the fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, said the move was tantamount to a military intervention, and vowed to attack any vessel that approaches the coast. After his meeting with <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> on Friday, <PERSON> Tarasov </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> `` strongly believes there are no military solutions to the <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> problems.'' <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, a spokesman said, expressed to <PERSON> Tarasov </PERSON> his `` full readiness to cooperate with the Soviet effort.'' The spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said <PERSON> Tarasov </PERSON> was working on `` a formula ... for stabilizing the security situation and lifting the blockade'' imposed by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and its allies on the 310-square-mile Christian heartland. Asked whether <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> would accept the deployment of observers at Christian ports to prevent arms supplies form reaching <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, as demanded by the Moslems, the source said: `` Would the other side accept observers to prevent the flow of weapons from <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>?'' A Moslem source said the Soviet diplomatic effort `` did not contradict'' the deployment of French warships in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. `` The Soviet effort is the carrot and the French naval buildup is the stick,'' the source said, also insisting on anonymity. He said the French flotilla in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> was `` a message'' to the Syrians and their allies that `` storming the -LRB- <ORGAN