<HEAD>Communists Reject Hungary, Poland-Style Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON> on Saturday rejected the type of reforms embraced by <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, and condemned foreign activists who participated in recent anti-government demonstrations. At a rally, <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON> said the party can not allow `` the weakening of the leading role'' of the Communists, the official <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. While no country was directly mentioned, <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON>' comments clearly were meant to draw the line between <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and the two Soviet bloc countries implementing the most daring reforms _ <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Both have committed themselves to a multi-party system and increasingly favor free-market economics. In <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, the first non-Communist prime minister in the Soviet bloc took office last week. On the foreign protesters, <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON> condemned `` the misuse of visits to <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> for interference in our internal affairs, as it was demonstrated on Aug. 21,'' said <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> riot police dispersed thousands of demonstrators Aug. 21, the 21st anniversary of the 1968 <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact invasion that crushed attempts to liberalize Communism in ways that resemble some present Soviet, Polish and Hungarian reforms. State news media said 370 people were detained, including 50 foreigners. At the rally Saturday at <LOCATION> Banska </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bystrica </LOCATION>, 300 miles east of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, Politburo member <PERSON> Ignac </PERSON> <PERSON> Janak </PERSON> condemned `` actions of ... so-called ` tourists' from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and some other countries,'' CTK reported. The Communist Party daily Rude Pravo said, `` they did not behave ... as normal tourists, such as come to <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> by the millions every year. Therefore a punishment must come.'' The Rude Pravo commentary appeared directed at two Hungarian activists. The government said Thursday that the rest of those detained had been released. The two _ identified as <PERSON> Tamas </PERSON> <PERSON> Deutsch </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gyoergy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kereny </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> FIDESZ </ORGANIZATION> political opposition group _ unfurled a banner at the demonstration proclaiming, `` Bolsheviks Came With Tanks, We Come With Flowers.'' <PERSON> Kereny </PERSON> also addressed the crowd before his arrest. <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> said the two would be tried for committing an offense against the public order. It did not say what the maximum sentence could be. The Hungarian news agency <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION>, in a report from <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, said the two were informed at the <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> city jail that they would be tried. Also present were the Hungarian consul and a <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Lzicar </PERSON>, an attorney known for his defense of prominent human rights advocate <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>. Both men submitted a formal complaint against their arrest, and the <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> guaranteed the two would appear at trial, said <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION>. Diplomatic sources said, however, that the two remained in custody. In <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, hundreds of <ORGANIZATION> FIDESZ </ORGANIZATION> supporters gathered in front of the Czechoslovak Embassy to protest the decision to try the two, and spokesmen said the group would continue the vigil. <PERSON> Janak </PERSON> also criticized Hungarian TV for airing interviews critical of the Soviet military intervention with officially disgraced Czechoslovaks on the night of the anniversary. Among those interviewed were the architect of the reforms, former <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, a prominent member of the Charter 77 human rights monitoring organization. `` Good neighborly relations, the spirit of mutual trust, respect and understanding are not built in a way demonstrated to us constantly by some foreign political journalists of Hungarian television,'' <PERSON> Janak </PERSON> said. When it aired initially in April, the <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> interview drew strong protest from the Czechoslovak leadership, which took power after the Soviet-led invasion. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> was one of five <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact countries that participated in the invasion. But its Communist leadership has been the only one within the pact to call the military intervention a mistake.
