<HEAD>Appeals Court Affirms Convictions in Talk Show Host's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The civil rights convictions of white supremacists <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> in the murder of radio talk show host <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Berg </PERSON> have been upheld by a federal appeals court. The 10th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> rejected the defendants' arguments that they participated in <PERSON> Berg </PERSON>'s murder because they hated the outspoken broadcaster as an individual and not because he was a Jew The two had contended their federal civil rights convictions and 150-year prison sentences should be overturned for that reason. `` No reversible error has been demonstrated,'' the appeals court said in its decision Friday. The court also rejected other arguments by the defendants, including that there was insufficient evidence to convict them and that their civil rights trial amounted to double jeopardy because their earlier racketeering trial included testimony about the <PERSON> Berg </PERSON> murder. <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> belonged to a group of white supremacists called The Order. They were convicted by a <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> U.S. District Court jury in November 1987 of violating the civil rights of <PERSON> Berg </PERSON>, 50, when he was gunned down in June 1984. They were indicted on the civil rights count, of interfering with a federally protected right resulting in death, because there is no federal murder charge. State prosecutors had decided there was insufficient evidence to try the two for murder. The two, along with several others, were also convicted of federal racketeering charges, which included allegations of the Berg killing, in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> in 1985. Their 150-year sentences for the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> convictions are to follow their racketeering sentences. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> was sentenced to 100 years and <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> to 40 years for the racketeering convictions, which were based on their roles in <PERSON> Berg </PERSON>'s death, bank robberies and counterfeiting Witnesses had testified that the murder was triggered by <PERSON> Berg </PERSON>'s on-air derision of the defendants' right-wing beliefs
