<HEAD>19 Reported Killed in Rebel Attack in Mozambique</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rebels attacked a southern town but were repelled by government forces, an official report said Saturday. It said at least 19 people were killed. About 200 rebels of the <ORGANIZATION> Mozambican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> launched the attack Thursday on <PERSON> Macia </PERSON>, about 55 miles north of the capital of <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION>, according to the government news agency AIM. At least 12 rebels and seven civilians were killed before government troops forced the guerrillas to retreat, AIM said, citing the <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION> daily newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Noticias </ORGANIZATION>. The report said nothing of government casualties. Noticias also reported that other people were killed by rebels who overran the central town of <LOCATION> Laubo </LOCATION> on Aug. 19. It did not say exactly how many people died. The rebels have been fighting since 1977 to undermine <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>'s leftist government. No government acknowledges supporting the rebels, who have devastated <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>'s economy with hit-and-run attacks on civilian and military targets. Rebel leaders and Mozambican clergymen representing the government of President <PERSON> Joaquim </PERSON> <PERSON> Chissano </PERSON> met in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> this month for preliminary peace talks, but no agreements were reported. The war has claimed an estimated 600,000 lives and displaced more than 1 million people.
