<HEAD>Fifteen Ultra-Orthodox Arrested For Sabbath Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police on Saturday detained 15 ultra-Orthodox Jews on suspicion of attacking cars driven by secular Jews in a mostly religious <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> neighborhood, a spokesman said. The ultra-Orthodox Jews were protesting what they consider a violation of the Sabbath, the Jewish day of rest lasting from sundown Friday until sundown Saturday. Jewish religious laws forbid any work or money transactions on Sabbath, and driving a car is considered a form of work. Police said 150 to 200 ultra-Orthodox Jews blocked the streets and attacked motorists in <LOCATION> Har </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nof </LOCATION> neighborhood. Thousands of ultra-Orthodox families populate Har Nof, which also is home to several hundred secular families. Police spokesman <PERSON> Uzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandouri </PERSON> said 15 ultra-Orthodox suspected of disturbing public order and an illegal gathering were detained. Six were teen-agers and three were released after questioning, he said. The last major wave of ultra-Orthodox protests in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> was in December 1987, when hundreds of religious Jews demonstrated every Saturday against movie theaters and other entertainment spots operating on Sabbath.
