<SECOND>AM-Silent March,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nostalgic March Criticizes `Legal Lynching' of Civil Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>LaserPhotos WX9, WX10 and WX12 ^By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 To the somber cadence of muffled drums, an estimated 35,000 people marched Saturday upon the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to protest what <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooks </PERSON> called `` the legal lynching of black <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s hope ... to become full partners in the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> dream.'' The march, aimed at spurring legislative `` remedies'' for four recent civil rights decisions by the high court, was fashioned in tone and dress after the historic `` Silent March'' 72 years ago in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. As then, men wore black and women and children wore white; as then, the marchers kept their lips sealed throughout the procession. The 1917 march of 8,000 people, led by W.E.B. <PERSON> DuBois </PERSON>, down Fifth Avenue elevated the 8-year-old National Association for the Advancement of Colored People to the forefront of the then-fledgling civil rights movement. Saturday's event, which drew nearly every major civil rights leader in the nation, may have restored that standing for an organization which lately has been criticized within the black community as staid and ineffective. `` For an organization that's dead, we did pretty good, did n't we? beamed Hooks as he looked upon the throng which gathered at the East Front of the Capitol for a rally after the silent march. Hooks claimed a turnout of 135,000 people; police estimates were far smaller. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Park Police put the number of marchers at 35,000; the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Capitol police said the crowd at the rally was 18,500. More than 200 civic, church and labor organizations had joined the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> in sponsoring the march. Individuals joining Hooks on the speaker's dais included the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON>, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Sourthern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Height </PERSON>, president of the Black Leadership Forum, and dozens of others. `` We come, presenting our bodies in silent protest, in a manner used in 1917 to protest the brutal lynching of black Americans in this nation,'' said Hooks. `` It is ironic that 72 years later, we find ourselves marching once more to protest the legal lynching of black <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s hope for a chance to become full partners in the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> dream. `` The five justices who voted on four separate occasions to roll back the clock on civil rights, by their actions, have unraveled the ropes used by black Americans to climb out of the valleys of economic segregation.'' In the view of civil rights lawyers, the four decisions this year seriously cut into the modern legal gains of minorities, particularly employment rights. In one case, <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> McLean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, the court sharply limited the power of minority men and women to sue private parties, including schools, for discrimatory practices. Similarly, the court's decision in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> vs. J. <ORGANIZATION> A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Croson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was seen as diluting job set-aside programs _ guaranteeing certain percentages of municipal projects to minority subcontractors _ and other affirmative action plans. March organizers also assailed the decision in <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wilks </PERSON>, which allowed white firefighters in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, to attack a consent decree calling for the promotion of blacks as a case of `` reverse discrimination.'' The fourth ruling, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s Cove vs. <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON>, was criticized as shifting the entire burden of proof in job discrimination cases to the victims of employer bias. <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> told the rally at the Capitol that `` the unions march today because we believe discrimination can not be eradicated from our society until there is equal employment opportunity for all Americans.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has often been the target of major demonstrations in the capital in recent years. An estimated 325,000 turned out last spring to urge the court to stand by its 1973 decision legalizing abortion. However, the court weeks later softened that ruling in a case seen as a victory for anti-abortion forces.
