<HEAD>AP Stylebook Editor, Administrator Christopher W. French</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> French </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> newsman and administrator for 23 years and editor of the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stylebook </ORGANIZATION> since 1980, has died at age 49. French's wife, <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON>, discovered his body at their home in this <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> suburb Friday after returning from a visit to relatives out of state. The cause of death was not immediately determined. As editor of the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stylebook </ORGANIZATION>, a 284-page manual that prescribes word usage, punctuation and other guidelines for news writing, French was an arbiter of journalistic style for news media across the nation. The Boston-born journalist was a political science graduate of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, where he studied under a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> scholarship. After four years of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> service, including stints as a gunnery, personnel and public relations officer, he joined the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> in 1966 as a newsman in the news service's <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, bureau In 1969, he was assigned to <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, the main <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> bureau. In 1971-72 he was a political reporter at the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> statehouse and helped cover the 1972 national presidential campaign, including the national party conventions. In November 1972 he was named <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> state editor, overseeing <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> news coverage throughout <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. French transferred in 1974 to the General Desk in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the central AP national news desk, where he worked as a national editor and supervisor. Six years later, he was named AP Stylebook editor. In that position, which he has recently shared as co-editor, he updated the manual annually, to include new subject areas and take account of changing times and usages. Among other editorial responsibilities at the General Desk, French was editor of the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION>, a compilation of reports on developments within the news industry that is transmitted weekly on AP wires. Since 1981, he also held the position of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Desk </ORGANIZATION> administrative assistant for technology. In that role, he acted as liaison between the editorial and technical staffs, and helped introduce new computer systems into the AP headquarters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Besides his wife, the former <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Quackenboss </PERSON>, he is survived by two daughters, <PERSON> Emily </PERSON> and <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON>; by a sister, <PERSON> Suzanne </PERSON> <PERSON> French </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Hopkinton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, and by his mother, <PERSON> Thelma </PERSON> <PERSON> Westerling </PERSON> French of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. A memorial service will be conducted at 2 p.m. Tuesday at <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Norwalk </LOCATION>. In lieu of flowers, the family asked that contributions be made to the donor's charity of choice.
