<HEAD>Pravda Slams Unofficial Soviet Press, Says Polish Communists Not
Through</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pravda on Saturday accused several unofficial newspapers that have sprung up under Kremlin reforms of using Western funds to press for the overthrow of the Soviet government. In another attack on liberal trends, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily also warned Poles that Polish Communists may have suffered a defeat, but nobody should write their political obituary. Pravda called for a crackdown on publications that carry `` systematic and vicious attacks on our party and its leadership.'' Among targets of Pravda's censure were papers put out by the self-styled opposition party <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, an independent Siberian news agency and unofficial journalists <PERSON> Lev </PERSON> <PERSON> Timofeyev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON>. Their press activities, which once would have brought them constant harassment and arrests, have flourished despite continuing obstacles under the Kremlin's policy of glasnost, or more openness. Commentator <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhukov </PERSON> listed among his complaints against the activist journalists `` truly blasphemous attacks on <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>,'' including pornographic verses. He denounced cooperation between unofficial journalists and Western radio and press, saying their Western support made them the equivalent of foreign publications put out without permission on Soviet territory. <PERSON> Zhukov </PERSON> also accused many of the unofficial publications of pirating their paper supplies and the use of copying facilities. Under a law passed July 31, calls for the violent overthrow of the Soviet government are criminal offenses. An earlier version also banned statements that `` discredited'' the government, but it was replaced. On <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Prava </PERSON> said `` extremist-minded people are hurrying to write off the Polish <ORGANI