<HEAD>US-Soviet Conference Urges Alliance To Fight Global Warming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SUNDANCE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> scientists, politicians and entertainers on Saturday urged their governments to forge an `` environmental security alliance'' to combat global warming. Actor-filmmaker <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Redford </PERSON>, who co-sponsored the four-day conference with the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION>, read a letter to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>: `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.S.R. </ORGANIZATION> are the two largest producers of greenhouse gases'' thought to cause global warming, <PERSON> Redford </PERSON> said. `` We should provide the leadership in the search for common solutions to the global warming problem as well as for the environmental security of the world.'' The letter was signed by <PERSON> Redford </PERSON> and space researcher <PERSON> Roald </PERSON> <PERSON> Segdeev </PERSON>, head of an 11-member Soviet delegation, who said the two nations must cooperate to undo the environmental damage they have incurred. `` For the crimes we've committed, as humans on the planet, we are sentenced to do this job. And I think it is a life-long sentence,'' <PERSON> Segdeev </PERSON> said. His comments ended the conference of Soviet and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> scientists, political leaders, environmentalists, filmmakers and authors. Among those attending were Sens. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wirth </PERSON>, D-Colo.; <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> Gov <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON>; astronomer <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sagan </PERSON>, former <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> <PERSON> Udall </PERSON>; and cartoonist <PERSON> Garry </PERSON> <PERSON> Trudeau </PERSON>. The attempt at `` greenhouse glasnost'' was not as much a scientific conference as it was an attempt to `` pass the baton'' from scientists to policy-shapers in both countries, who need to take action, <PERSON> Redford </PERSON> said. During the conference, scientists predicted that the greenhouse effect, caused by rising levels of atmospheric carbon dioxide and other gases produced by industrial societies, could raise global temperatures by 2 to 10 degrees over the next century. That could alter worldwide weather patterns and cause the melting of the polar ice caps, flooding coastal regions. To combat the rise of carbon dioxide, much of which comes from the burning of fossil fuels, the letter proposes the two superpowers form an `` environmental security alliance'' to: _ Promote energy-efficient technology _ Halt production and use by the year 2000 of chlorofluorocarbons, another group of greenhouse gases, and `` substantially reduce'' carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases _ Reduce the rate of worldwide deforestation and start the planting of trees in unforested areas The letter was accompanied by a conference report detailing specific strategies for reducing global warming. In the past, <ORGANIZATION> Redford </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> For </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, a private environmental mediation group based at his Sundance resort in central <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, has tackled offshore drilling in the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, the construction of power plants in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> and air quality issues.
