<HEAD>NASA Official Forsees `Second Golden Age' Of Space Exploration</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Voyager-Neptune, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Voyager 2's <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION> encounter marks the last planetary flyby by a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> spacecraft, but missions to <PERSON> Venus </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Jupiter </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mars </ORGANIZATION> mean <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will keep exploring space, a <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> official said Saturday. `` We are embarking on the second golden age of space science,'' said <PERSON> Lennard </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON>, the agency's associate administrator for space science and applications. `` What's coming up is an era of unprecedented excitement and activity.'' The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> plans to launch 35 space science flights in the next five years _ the highest launch rate ever _ and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> spacecraft will be exploring planets continuously from next year until 2006, <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> said during a visit to <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s Jet Propulsion Laboratory. <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> was at the lab to watch Voyager 2's brush with <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION> last Thursday night _ the probe's final encounter after it explored Jupiter in 1979, <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> in 1981 and Uranus in 1986. `` In many ways, this is the end of an era, the last time we will see a planet for a first time, the end of the reconnaissance phase of planetary explorations,'' he said. There are no plans to explore Pluto, the only planet still not visited by a spacecraft But <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> listed several missions that will orbit planets rather than fly past them: _ <ORGANIZATION> Magellan </ORGANIZATION>, launched from a space shuttle last May, arrives at <LOCATION> Venus </LOCATION> next August and will study that planet for several years _ <ORGANIZATION> Galileo </ORGANIZATION> will be launched from the shuttle <LOCATION> Atlantis </LOCATION> on Oct. 12, arriving in orbit around Jupiter in 1996 and studying the planet until the end of the century _ The <ORGANIZATION> Hubble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telescope </ORGANIZATION> is due for launch from a shuttle next March, and is so powerful that from its orbit around <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> it will be able to `` observe the universe back to the beginning of time,'' <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> said _ Mars Observer will be launched in 1992, reaching the red planet in 1993 and studying it until 1996 _ <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> has asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to approve the Comet Rendevous-Asteroid Flyby and <ORGANIZATION> Cassini </ORGANIZATION> missions, <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> CRAF </ORGANIZATION> would fly past an asteroid, then orbit a comet from 2000 through 2002, <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> said. The similar spacecraft on the <ORGANIZATION> Cassini </ORGANIZATION> mission would drop a probe onto <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION>'s moon Titan, then orbit <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> from 2002 through 2006. <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> disputed assertions that unmanned space exploration will suffer financially because of the shuttle program, saying that 70 percent to 80 percent of non-military shuttle flights will be dedicated to space science. <PERSON> Fisk </PERSON> said space science studies suffered in recent years not from a lack of funds, but because of delays in developing the shuttle and the 1986 explosion that destroyed the shuttle Challenger and halted launches until last fall.
