<HEAD>Congressman Says Steel Deal Violates Trade Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> congressman asked the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> Friday to investigate a <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> ruling he says would allow <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies to import South African steel for construction of a bridge across the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> Ship Channel. <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, a Democrat, said the decision by Customs' Commercial Rulings Division appears to go against the Anti-Apartheid Act of 1986, which prohibits the importation of South African steel and iron into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. According to <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, the ruling would allow two contractors hired by the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Houton </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Traylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, to import nearly 3.1 million pounds of steel from a South African company for the bridge project. Customs spokeswoman <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> said the agency was not prepared to comment late Friday on <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>'s inquiries. She said she could not confirm the substance of the ruling and officials at the division were not available for comment late Friday. The $ 91 million bridge would be the costliest state funded road work in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> history. According to <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, the ruling was issued July 14. `` Considering the fact that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and many other public officials both statewide and nationally have have gone on record opposing the inhumane system of apartheid and the purchase of materials derived from the exploitive use of cheap leabor, I can not even begin to comprehend this decision,'' said <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> has also asked <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dedman </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, for an explanation. `` I am at a loss to understand why the <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> would apparently not only pass over the American steel industry and its workers, but also indirectly support <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s apartheid government,'' <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> wrote <PERSON> Dedman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> has asked <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> to determine whether the Commercial Rulings Division has the jurisdiction to make such a ruling, and on what basis it made its decision. He also wants to known when the contract was signed, the name of the South African company, and whether the ruling violates the Anti-Apartheid Act of 1986 or any other laws on trade with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The Anti-Apartheid Act of 1986 is aimed at curtailing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> because of that country's system of racial separation.
