<FIRST>r w AM-CFTC-SoybeanSqueeze     08-26 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CFTC-Soybean Squeeze,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Sees No Conflict in CBOT Soybean Emergency; Senator Skeptical</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A version has run on financial circuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that it found no examples of self-dealing by officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> during last month's forced liquidation of soybean futures contracts. But the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said a preliminary report by the commission raised possible conflict-of-interest questions about several of the officials who voted to require traders to reduce their holdings of contracts calling for future delivery of soybeans to them _ `` long'' positions. `` The <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> must question those <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> directors participating in the July soybean decision whose affiliated firms held net short positions in the July soybean contract in house or customer accounts,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., in a statement issued by his office `` Credibility is paramount for exchanges in carrying out their self-regulatory functions. The public will not tolerate self-dealing or conflict of interest by exchange directors or insiders,'' the <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> statement said. Holders of `` short'' positions, promises to deliver beans they do not own, would benefit from an order like the one issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> on July 11. One who holds a short position can can buy and deliver beans, or he can buy an offsetting `` long'' position. Generally such a trader is betting on a fall in price and the ability to buy an offsetting contract at a price lower than he paid for his original contract, thus making a profit. If the `` longs'' are forced to sell, the price of the contract declines and the `` shorts'' can fulfill their obligations cheaper than they would otherwise. The order forcing `` longs'' to sell touched off wild swings in soybean prices and sparked sharp criticism by farm groups and traders who saw the value of their holdings drop. The <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> has said it acted after consulting the commission because Italian grain merchant <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finanziaria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.p.A. </ORGANIZATION>, failed to reduce its large holdings in the July soybean market voluntarily. Officials of the exchange have said they were worried that there were not enough beans to fulfill all delivery commitments in the final days of the contract. The order required traders to reduce their long positions to 1 million bushels and was widely perceived as a move to prevent <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> from cornering the market _ that is, forcing other traders into a position of having to deliver beans to <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> where <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> was the only source of beans. Such a situation, if <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> could maintain it, would all but enable <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> to name its own price to let the other traders off the hook. Stock and commodity exchanges have rules aimed at banning `` corners.'' <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> has denied any wrongdoing or intention to corner the market and has bitterly critized the board's action. `` We continue to believe that is was totally unnecessary for the board to take its emergency action,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON>, an executive with <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> subsidiary. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> supports Sen. <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>'s call for further investigartion by the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> into the matter.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakes </PERSON>, a spokesman for the exchange, said that even though directors may have represented firms whose customers held short July soybean positions `` they're not involved in the decision-making of their customers.'' The commission said it found no director who appeared to trade for the purpose of profiting personally, or through an affiliated firm, from prior knowledge of the July 11 order. One director excused himself before deliberations began because he held a spread position _ both long and short _ in July soybeans. His affiliated firm also had net short positions for itself and customers. The commission's preliminary report was contained in a 36-page letter to <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> from Chairwoman <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>. It said investigators intend to conduct more interviews.
</TEXT>
