 <PERSON> Philippe </PERSON> <PERSON> Petit </PERSON> hopes his high-wire walk to the Eiffel Tower on Saturday will lift the hearts of the thousands watching, inspire them to try the impossible and demonstrate real freedom as <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> celebrates justice and liberty. <PERSON> Petit </PERSON>, known for his illicit and joyous walks between the towers of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>' Notre Dame Cathedral and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s World Trade Center, said Friday he is ready for the walk that will take him 2,300 feet from the Palais de Chaillot to the Eiffel Tower's second level. `` I'm impatient to begin, to do something I've dreamt of doing my whole life,'' said <PERSON> Petit </PERSON>, who was born 40 years ago in a suburb west of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and now lives in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Rushing between the barber and a technical check of the rigging, the aerialist took a moment to reflect on the spectacle that is a highlight of French celebrations commemorating the bicentennial of the Declaration of the Rights of Man. `` People hear the word funambulist and they think of the circus, but that's not at all what I do,'' he said, gazing at the wire strung fine as a spider's web. `` I want people to be enlightened by a vision, I want to uplift their minds and hearts.'' <PERSON> Petit </PERSON>, who shares with dancers a passion for poetic gestures and movements that transfigure, is asked with deadly monotony about the danger involved in his work. The question bores him. `` I take no risks. I've been preparing for this for 10 years and the technical aspects for six months,'' said <PERSON> Petit </PERSON>, who did all his own rigging and studied blueprints, photos and charts. His walk was authorized by <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> who will be waiting on the tower's second level, 330 feet above the ground. <PERSON> Pe