<HEAD>Taiwan, U.S. Agree To Fishing Pact In North Pacific</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> have signed an agreement that will enable federal authorities to track Taiwanese fishing vessels by satellite in an effort to reduce illegal salmon fishing in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. The agreement, signed Thursday, calls for radio transponders to be installed in Taiwanese boats, allowing satellite surveillance of <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> fishing fleet. It also permits <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials to board those ships. In addition, the pact provides for observers to monitor the driftnet fishermen's impact on dolphin, porpoise, seal and other marine mammal populations. `` Tough negotiating pays off,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Murkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>. `` I believe signing this agreement lays the cornerstone for an overall effort to secure our fisheries and protect a most vital resource.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has accused <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> fishermen of using driftnets to deplete the North Pacific of its rich marine resources, especially the anadromous species of salmon that spawn in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Conservationists have criticized the driftnets, some of which are 40 miles long, for their `` incidental'' catches of thousands of sea birds, seals and other animals. Some Northwest fishermen said they liked what they heard Friday about the pact. `` It's another step forward,'' said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Collier </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seafood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Processors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. But at least one environmental group warned the agreement does n't go far enough and that no such pact has been signed with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> as a congressionally mandated deadline approaches `` You just ca n't trust these driftnetters,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Reichman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> ecology coordinator for <ORGANIZATION> Greenpeace </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Collier </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seafood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Processors </ORGANIZATION> represents 85 percent of the processors in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, estimated 7 million salmon were taken illegally during 1987. The agreement was signed for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Laux </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Ding </PERSON> <PERSON> Mou-shih </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s representative in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C </ORGANIZATION>. Diplomatic letters to finalize the agreement were signed Friday. The institute serves as the unofficial <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassy in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government severed diplomatic ties with <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> in 1978. `` The key here is this monitoring equipment will go a long way to determining where those fish are caught and give us more confidence in managing the resource,'' said <PERSON> Vince </PERSON> <PERSON> Curry </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Factory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trawlers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. By signing the pact, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> beat a Monday deadline set by a 1987 law that threatened sanctions if <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> did not agree to monitor their <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> fishing fleets and enforce bans on taking high-seas salmon. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> signed an agreement in June that called for the experimental use of transponders and a cadre of 47 observers _ nine American, five Canadian and 33 Japanese _ to monitor driftnet damage to marine mammal populations. Similar details were not available Friday for the pact with <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that talks with the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> had been suspended until Aug. 29. Similar agreements to those accepted by the Japanese and Taiwanese have been proposed. <PERSON> Yu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yu-hsien </PERSON>, chairman of <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>, said in <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> that his government agreed to the pact for the sake of 600,000 fishermen on the island who depend on exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, mostly of tuna and shrimp.
