<HEAD>Sugar Prices Swing Between Sweet and Sour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Sugar futures prices fluctuated widely on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as traders bought into the market on news of a large purchase by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and bailed out on reports the European sugar beet crop may exceed last year's. Adding to sugar price instabilty is what analysts say is the inability of the October futures contract to sustain advances at a price higher than 14 cents a pound. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Savaiko </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said traders view the sugar market as bullish, but are afraid to buy contracts. He said there wo n't be a significant change in trader attitudes until Third World countries are willing to pay high prices created by the delicate balance of supply and demand. World sugar stocks are low due to several years of poor sugar-cane crops and steadily rising consumption. <PERSON> Savaiko </PERSON> said a factor keeping Third World countries out of the sugar market is that sugar is often bought and sold for dollars, making it expensive in terms of those country's currencies. A Third World leader, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, entered the market for 200,000 tons of refined sugar. But it had been expected that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> would purchase as much as 500,000 tons of raw and refined sugar, so the smaller figure was a disappointment. Sugar prices fell sharply on projections by F.O. Licht, the West German sugar statistical firm, that European sugar production will increase from the 30.1 million tons produced last year to 32.3 million tons. Licht also said weather in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had been excellent, resulting in an improved crop of sugar in that country, reducing its import needs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Copper</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Copper futures prices continued their upward spiral as production problems plagued producers worldwide while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Japanese demand remained strong. As of July, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rod and mill use of copper _ two-thirds of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> copper consumption _ rose 10 percent from the year-earlier level, analysts said. Besides a paralyzing strike in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, copper production is hampered by a strike at the <LOCATION> Highland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> mines in <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>; the bankruptcy of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Cananea </LOCATION> mine which is expected to be closed up to three months; and the shutdown of the <LOCATION> Bougainville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Papua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> mine due to terrorist sabotage.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Grain and Soybeans</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and Soybean futures contracts settled into a narrow trading range as expectations for near normal harvest this fall become stronger because of rainy weather in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Energy</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Petroleum futures prices struggled in a market that has been slow all summer. Analysts and traders said uncertainty over the actual demand for petroleum products in the second half of the year makes the price outlook uncertain. A report from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> showing a surprisingly large increase in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil inventories did not help prices.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Precious metals</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Trading in gold and silver remained slack due to a strong dollar and little evidence of rising inflation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Livestock and meat</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Cattle futures turned in a mixed performance as firm cash prices weakened because of concerns over plentiful supplies. Pork futures continued their steady gain on the strength of cash prices.
