<SECOND>PM-Stocks-Investors,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Investors Returning To Stock Market, But Cautiously</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Though some first-time investors who were scared away by the stock market crash two years ago never returned, those who remained got their reward, market watchers said. The record high of 2,734.64 in the Dow Jones industrials average Thursday once again pointed out the value of a long-term investment strategy, these observers said. On Friday, the average slipped back 2.28 points to 2,732.36. Anyone who held stocks for the past two years has about broken even, while people who panicked and sold at the bottom took big losses. `` A person has to live through a market break to fully appreciate what can happen in the next market peak,'' said <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Janke </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit group of individual investors and investment-club members. Media accounts of small investors abandoning the stock market after the crash were overblown, says <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cloonan </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Individual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION>. The shrinkage in his members' stock portfolios was mainly from a drop in the market price of shares, not stock sales, he said. Industry figures show that individual investors did leave the market after the crash, but that many have since returned. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, an average of 37 million shares a day were traded by retail, as opposed to institutional, customers on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in August 1987. That November, after the crash, the average number of daily retail trades dropped to 31 million. The average for all of 1988 was 29 million retail trades a day. But the figure jumped to 39 million a day from January to June of this year, the latest figures available. `` The retail investor definitely is back,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Monahan </PERSON>, director of industry studies for the industry group. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Scidmore </PERSON>, a small investor in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, said he believes the Dow high could scare some investors away from the market rather than lure new ones. `` The little investors, you can to go any -LRB- investment -RRB- club now and they're chewing their fingers and saying the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION>'s up now and it's due for a fall,'' said <PERSON> Scidmore </PERSON>, who is retired and belongs to two investment clubs. <PERSON> Scidmore </PERSON> is not frightened away himself. `` If you're in it for the long run, so what?'' he said. `` It goes up and it goes down.'' Individual investors feel unable to compete with market professionals and institutions, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON>, a portfolio manager with <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Counsel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, an independent financial consultant in <LOCATION> Charlottesville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` The individual investor feels that he's sort of outside looking in, that the experts know what's going on, they know where to look for takeover candidates,'' <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> said. `` The individual feels that he does n't get a fair shake.'' <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> believes the Dow high will do little to lure more small investors back to the market. He said the reaction of many is, `` Well, I missed it and I should have been in on it but it's too late now.'' `` I think if we had a recession and we got into it for couple of quarters, and of course the stock market would probably be lower, then I think you'd see the individual investor coming back,'' he said. On the flip side of that coin, <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> said that if the Dow continues its upward climb and sets more records, the trauma of the crash could fade into the back of many investors' minds. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunnan </PERSON>, an author of investment books, agreed that many individual investors have returned to the market. But, she said, ``'87 was n't that long ago, so you're not going to see all of them jump back in.'' She said small investors should have learned at least one lesson from the crash. `` I think they should watch the market every single day and not let it ride, and if they see a dip and they've already made their profit to not be shy or greedy and take that profit,'' she said.
