<FIRST>d f PM-BasketCase     08-26 0842</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Basket Case,0866</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Tisket, A Tasket, Who Controls Stocks In a Basket?</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Like kids tussling over an Easter basket of goodies, two federal agencies and the financial exchanges they regulate are squaring off over a new money-making product for investors known as a `` stock basket.'' On one side are the stock exchanges and their overseer, the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, created in the depths of the Depression to regulate stocks and bonds and protect the people who invest in them. On the other side is the newer <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and its charges, the boisterous markets that deal in commodities such as soybeans, pork bellies and silver. The product at issue is technically called an `` index participation,'' but it resembles a basket of stocks because it allows investors to buy or sell something with a value tied to broad stock market indexes, such as the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Poors </ORGANIZATION> 500. That's why it's also called a stock basket. A week ago, a federal appeals court in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> ruled the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> overstepped itself in authorizing three exchanges, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, to trade stock baskets. The 7th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> held that the new financial instruments are futures contracts and should be regulated by the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> _ throwing doubt on the legitimacy of the baskets traded on the stock exchanges. `` It's like being married for five years and finding out the preacher was n't licensed,'' says <ORGANIZATION> AMEX </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leibler </PERSON>, `` and if you want to get married again, you have to do it in a different state.'' While the new products have n't been a raging success since trading began May 12 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, some observers they represent the future of the securities industry. New product development became particularly important after the 1987 stock crash, which depressed the business of many investment firms and forced them to seek ways of luring investors back. The American and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> exchanges, as well as the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Options </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, thought one answer would be stock baskets. Unlike stocks, investors never actually buy the securities that make up a stock index and therefore have no ownership rights. But unlike commodity futures, there's no settlement or termination date. The basket can be held indefinitely. For example, an investor could buy a basket tied to the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P 500 index when it has a value of 300. A monetary value is assigned to each contract, usually sold in lots of 100. If the value was $ 30 -LRB- or one-tenth the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P 500 index -RRB-, the basket would be worth $ 3,000 and if the index went up 10 points, the investor would make a profit of $ 100 because the lot of 100 was now worth $ 3,100. But the stock baskets also represent a challenge to similar products offered by the two major futures exchanges in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>: the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Those two exchanges claimed the stock baskets ought to be regulated by the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> and the appeals court agreed, saying the law creating the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> clearly gave it authority in this case. `` Our feeling is the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> is best equipped to regulate futures products because it has the expertise,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connell </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Board of Trade. To <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mass </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> finance subcommittee, who has tried unsuccessfully to push market reform legislation, the ruling `` highlights the problems inherent in this turf battle between the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>,'' said a <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> spokesman. But <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Medero </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>'s general counsel, said: `` I do n't think the people here feel it is a turf battle _ not on the commissioner or staff level The turf battle may be more between the securities exchanges and the commodities exchanges, rather than the agencies, which is fine. That's competition.'' The <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> did file court papers in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> lawsuit stating its view that stock baskets are futures contracts, and if the ruling is appealed Ms. <PERSON> Medero </PERSON> said `` we would reiterate our position.'' Spokesmen for both stock and futures exchanges stopped short of saying another agency might not treat them fairly but indicated they preferred to deal with the one they've known for years. Stock exchange officials noted that margins _ the amount of money or collateral that must be put up to buy securities _ are less stringent in the futures markets. Under CFTC rules, said <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Giordano </PERSON>, president of the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> exchange, the stock basket `` wo n't be a product that appeals to the public investor _ the man in the street. It'll be more speculative, have higher risk and would not enjoy the protection of public investor rules that have been cultivated by the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> for 50 years.'' The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> has yet to announce whether it will appeal the ruling by the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> federal court. `` I really ca n't tell you until we do it,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonson </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s solicitor, although he confirmed that the agency was discussing alternatives with the exchanges.
